U||The Wood
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||They cut it down, and where the pitch-black aisles
U||Of forest night had hid eternal things,
U||They scal’d the sky with tow’rs and marble piles
U||To make a city for their revellings.
U||White and amazing to the lands around
U||That wondrous wealth of domes and turrets rose;
U||Crystal and ivory, sublimely crown’d
U||With pinnacles that bore unmelting snows.
U||And through its halls the pipe and sistrum rang,
U||While wine and riot brought their scarlet stains;
U||Never a voice of elder marvels sang,
U||Nor any eye call’d up the hills and plains.
U||Thus down the years, till on one purple night
U||A drunken minstrel in his careless verse
U||Spoke the vile words that should not see the light,
U||And stirr’d the shadows of an ancient curse.
U||Forests may fall, but not the dusk they shield;
U||So on the spot where that proud city stood,
U||The shuddering dawn no single stone reveal’d,
U||But fled the blackness of a primal wood.
