U||Unda; or, The Bride of the Sea
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||Respectfully Dedicated with Permission to MAURICE WINTER MOE, Esq.
U||A Dull, Dark, Drear, Dactylic Delirium in Sixteen Silly, Senseless, Sickly Stanzas
U||“Ego, canus, lunam cano.”
U||—Maevius Bavianus.
U||Black loom the crags of the uplands behind me;
U||Dark are the sands of the far-stretching shore.
U||Dim are the pathways and rocks that remind me
U||Sadly of years in the lost nevermore.
U||Soft laps the ocean on wave-polish’d boulder;
U||Sweet is the sound and familiar to me.
U||Here, with her head gently bent to my shoulder,
U||Walk’d I with Unda, the Bride of the Sea.
U||Bright was the morn of my youth when I met her,
U||Sweet as the breeze that blew in o’er the brine.
U||Swift was I captur’d in Love’s strongest fetter,
U||Glad to be hers, and she glad to be mine.
U||Never a question ask’d I where she wander’d,
U||Never a question ask’d she of my birth:
U||Happy as children, we thought not nor ponder’d,
U||Glad with the bounty of ocean and earth.
U||Once when the moonlight play’d soft ’mid the billows,
U||High on the cliff o’er the waters we stood,
U||Bound was her hair with a garland of willows,
U||Pluck’d by the fount in the bird-haunted wood.
U||Strangely she gaz’d on the surges beneath her,
U||Charm’d by the sound or entranc’d by the light.
U||Then did the waves a wild aspect bequeath her,
U||Stern as the ocean and weird as the night.
U||Coldly she left me, astonish’d and weeping,
U||Standing alone ’mid the regions she bless’d:
U||Down, ever downward, half gliding, half creeping,
U||Stole the sweet Unda in oceanward quest.
U||Calm grew the sea, and tumultuous beating
U||Turn’d to a ripple, as Unda the fair
U||Trod the wet sands in affectionate greeting,
U||Beckon’d to me, and no longer was there!
U||Long did I pace by the banks where she vanish’d:
U||High climb’d the moon, and descended again.
U||Grey broke the dawn till the sad night was banish’d,
U||Still ach’d my soul with its infinite pain.
U||All the wide world have I search’d for my darling,
U||Scour’d the far deserts and sail’d distant seas.
U||Once on the wave while the tempest was snarling,
U||Flash’d a fair face that brought quiet and ease.
U||Ever in restlessness onward I stumble,
U||Seeking and pining, scarce heeding my way.
U||Now have I stray’d where the wide waters rumble,
U||Back to the scene of the lost yesterday.
U||Lo! the red moon from the ocean’s low hazes
U||Rises in ominous grandeur to view.
U||Strange is its face as my tortur’d eye gazes
U||O’er the vast reaches of sparkle and blue.
U||Straight from the moon to the shore where I’m sighing
U||Grows a bright bridge, made of wavelets and beams.
U||Frail may it be, yet how simple the trying;
U||Wand’ring from earth to the orb of sweet dreams.
U||What is yon face in the moonlight appearing;
U||Have I at last found the maiden that fled?
U||Out on the beam-bridge my footsteps are nearing
U||Her whose sweet beckoning hastens my tread.
U||Currents surround me, and drowsily swaying,
U||Far on the moon-path I seek the sweet face.
U||Eagerly hasting, half panting, half praying,
U||Forward I reach for the vision of grace.
U||Murmuring waters about me are closing,
U||Soft the sweet vision advances to me:
U||Done are my trials; my heart is reposing
U||Safe with my Unda, the Bride of the Sea.
U||Epilogue
U||As the rash fool, a prey of Unda’s art,
U||Drown thro’ the passion of his fever’d heart,
U||So are our youth, inflam’d by tempters fair,
U||Bereft of reason and the manly air.
U||How sad the sight of Strephon’s virile grace
U||Turn’d to confusion at his Chloë’s face,
U||And e’er Pelides, dear to Grecian eyes,
U||Sulking for loss of his thrice-cherish’d prize.
U||Brothers, attend! If cares too sharply vex,
U||Gain rest by shunning the destructive sex!
