U||To Edward John Moreton Drax Plunkett,
U||Eighteenth Baron Dunsany
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||As when the sun above a dusky wold
U||Springs into sight, and turns the gloom to gold,
U||Lights with his magic beams the dew-deck’d bow’rs,
U||And wakes to life the gay responsive flow’rs;
U||So now o’er realms where dark’ning dulness lies,
U||In solar state see shining Plunkett rise!
U||Monarch of Fancy! whose ethereal mind
U||Mounts fairy peaks, and leaves the throng behind;
U||Whose soul untainted bursts the bounds of space,
U||And leads to regions of supernal grace;
U||Can any praise thee with too strong a tone,
U||Who in this age of folly gleam’st alone?
U||Thy quill, Dunsany, with an art divine
U||Recalls the gods to each deserted shrine;
U||From mystic air a novel pantheon makes,
U||And with new spirits fills the meads and brakes;
U||With thee we wander thro’ primeval bow’rs,
U||For thou hast brought earth’s childhood back, and ours!
U||How leaps the soul, with sudden bliss increas’d,
U||When led by thee to lands beyond the East!
U||Sick of this sphere, in crime and conflict old,
U||We yearn for wonders distant and untold;
U||O’er Homer’s page a second time we pore,
U||And rack our brains for gleams of infant lore:
U||But all in vain—for valiant tho’ we strive
U||No common means these pictures can revive.
U||Then dawns Dunsany with celestial light,
U||And fulgent visions break upon our sight:
U||His barque enchanted each sad spirit bears
U||To shores of gold, beyond the reach of cares.
U||No earthly trammels now our thoughts may chain;
U||For childhood’s fancy hath come back again!
U||What glitt’ring worlds now wait our eager eyes!
U||What roads untrodden beckon thro’ the skies!
U||Wonders on wonders line the gorgeous ways,
U||And glorious vistas greet the ravish’d gaze;
U||Mountains of clouds, castles of crystal dreams,
U||Ethereal cities and Elysian streams;
U||Temples of blue, where myriad stars adore
U||Forgotten gods of aeons gone before!
U||Such are thine arts, Dunsany, such thy skill,
U||That scarce terrestrial seems thy moving quill;
U||Can man, and man alone, successful draw
U||Such scenes of wonder and domains of awe?
U||Our hearts, enraptur’d, fix thy mind’s abode
U||In high Pegāna; hail thee as a god;
U||And sure, can aught more high or godlike be
U||Than such a fancy as resides in thee?
U||Delighted Pan a friend and peer perceives
U||As thy sweet music stirs the sylvan leaves;
U||The Nine, transported, bless thy golden lyre,
U||Approve thy fancy, and applaud thy fire;
U||Whilst Jove himself assumes a brother’s tone,
U||And vows the pantheon equal to his own.
U||Dunsany, may thy days be glad and long;
U||Replete with visions, and atune with song;
U||May thy rare notes increasing millions cheer,
U||Thy name beloved, and thy mem’ry dear!
U||’Tis thou who hast in hours of dulness brought
U||New charms of language, and new gems of thought;
U||Hast with a poet’s grace enrich’d the earth
U||With aureate dreams as noble as thy birth.
U||Grateful we name thee, bright with fix’d renown,
U||The fairest jewel in Hibernia’s crown.
