U||To Clark Ashton Smith, Esq.,
U||upon His Phantastick Tales,
U||Verses, Pictures, and Sculptures
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||A time-black tower against dim banks of cloud;
U||Around its base the pathless, pressing wood.
U||Shadow and silence, moss and mould, enshroud
U||Grey, age-fell’d slabs that once as cromlechs stood.
U||No fall of foot, no song of bird awakes
U||The lethal aisles of sempiternal night,
U||Tho’ oft with stir of wings the dense air shakes,
U||As in the tower there glows a pallid light.
U||For here, apart, dwells one whose hands have wrought
U||Strange eidola that chill the world with fear;
U||Whose graven runes in tones of dread have taught
U||What things beyond the star-gulfs lurk and leer.
U||Dark Lord of Averoigne—whose windows stare
U||On pits of dream no other gaze could bear!
