U||Revelation
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||In a vale of light and laughter,
U||Shining ’neath the friendly sun,
U||Where fulfilment follow’d after
U||Ev’ry hope or dream begun;
U||Where an Aidenn gay and glorious,
U||Beckon’d down the winsome way;
U||There my soul, o’er pain victorious,
U||Laugh’d and lingered—yesterday.
U||Green and narrow was my valley,
U||Temper’d with a verdant shade;
U||Sun-deck’d brooklets musically
U||Sparkled thro’ each glorious glade;
U||And at night the stars serenely
U||Glow’d betwixt the boughs o’erhead,
U||While Astarte, calm and queenly,
U||Floods of fairy radiance shed.
U||There amid the tinted bowers,
U||Raptur’d with the opiate spell
U||Of the grasses, ferns, and flowers,
U||Poppy, phlox and pimpernel,
U||Long I lay, entranc’d and dreaming,
U||Pleas’d with Nature’s bounteous store,
U||Till I mark’d the shaded gleaming
U||Of the sky, and yearn’d for more.
U||Eagerly the branches tearing,
U||Clear’d I all the space above,
U||Till the bolder gaze, high faring,
U||Scann’d the naked skies of Jove;
U||Deeps unguess’d now shone before me,
U||Splendid beam’d the solar car;
U||Wings of fervid fancy bore me
U||Out beyond the farthest star.
U||Reaching, gasping, wishing, longing
U||For the pageant brought to sight,
U||Vain I watch’d the gold orbs thronging
U||Round celestial poles of light.
U||Madly on a moonbeam ladder
U||Heav’n’s abyss I sought to scale,
U||Ever wiser, ever sadder,
U||As the fruitless task would fail.
U||Then, with futile striving sated,
U||Veer’d my soul to earth again,
U||Well content that I was fated
U||For a fair, yet low domain;
U||Pleasing thoughts of glad tomorrows,
U||Like the blissful moments past,
U||Lull’d to rest my transient sorrows,
U||Still’d my godless greed at last.
U||But my downward glance, returning,
U||Shrank in fright from what it spy’d;
U||Slopes in hideous torment burning,
U||Terror in the brooklet’s tide:
U||For the dell, of shade denuded
U||By my desecrating hand,
U||’Neath the bare sky blaz’d and brooded
U||As a lost, accursed land.
