U||Psychopompos: A Tale in Rhyme
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||I am He who howls in the night;
U||I am He who moans in the snow;
U||I am He who hath never seen light;
U||I am He who mounts from below.
U||My car is the car of Death;
U||My wings are the wings of dread;
U||My breath is the north wind’s breath;
U||My prey are the cold and the dead.
U||In old Auvergne, when schools were poor and few,
U||And peasants fancy’d what they scarcely knew,
U||When lords and gentry shunn’d their Monarch’s throne
U||For solitary castles of their own,
U||There dwelt a man of rank, whose fortress stood
U||In the hush’d twilight of a hoary wood.
U||De Blois his name; his lineage high and vast,
U||A proud memorial of an honour’d past;
U||But curious swains would whisper now and then
U||That Sieur De Blois was not as other men.
U||In person dark and lean, with glossy hair,
U||And gleaming teeth that he would often bare,
U||With piercing eye, and stealthy roving glance,
U||And tongue that clipt the soft, sweet speech of France;
U||The Sieur was little lov’d and seldom seen,
U||So close he kept within his own demesne.
U||The castle servants, few, discreet, and old,
U||Full many a tale of strangeness might have told;
U||But bow’d with years, they rarely left the door
U||Wherein their sires and grandsires serv’d before.
U||Thus gossip rose, as gossip rises best,
U||When mystery imparts a keener zest;
U||Seclusion oft the poison tongue attracts,
U||And scandal prospers on a dearth of facts.
U||’Twas said, the Sieur had more than once been spy’d
U||Alone at midnight by the river’s side,
U||With aspect so uncouth, and gaze so strange,
U||That rustics cross’d themselves to see the change;
U||Yet none, when press’d, could clearly say or know
U||Just what it was, or why they trembled so.
U||De Blois, as rumour whisper’d, fear’d to pray,
U||Nor us’d his chapel on the Sabbath day;
U||Howe’er this may have been, ’twas known at least
U||His household had no chaplain, monk, or priest.
U||But if the Master liv’d in dubious fame,
U||Twice fear’d and hated was his noble Dame;
U||As dark as he, in features wild and proud,
U||And with a weird supernal grace endow’d,
U||The haughty mistress scorn’d the rural train
U||Who sought to learn her source, but sought in vain.
U||Old women call’d her eyes too bright by half,
U||And nervous children shiver’d at her laugh;
U||Richard, the dwarf (whose word had little weight),
U||Vow’d she was like a serpent in her gait,
U||Whilst ancient Pierre (the aged often err)
U||Laid all her husband’s mystery to her.
U||Still more absurd were those odd mutter’d things
U||That calumny to curious list’ners brings;
U||Those subtle slanders, told with downcast face,
U||And muffled voice—those tales no man may trace;
U||Tales that the faith of old wives can command,
U||Tho’ always heard at sixth or seventh hand.
U||Thus village legend darkly would imply
U||That Dame De Blois possess’d an evil eye;
U||Or going further, furtively suggest
U||A lurking spark of sorcery in her breast;
U||Old Mère Allard (herself half witch) once said
U||The lady’s glance work’d strangely on the dead.
U||So liv’d the pair, like many another two
U||That shun the crowd, and shrink from public view.
U||They scorn’d the doubts by ev’ry peasant shewn,
U||And ask’d but one thing—to be let alone!
U||’Twas Candlemas, the dreariest time of year,
U||With fall long gone, and spring too far to cheer,
U||When little Jean, the bailiff’s son and heir,
U||Fell sick and threw the doctors in despair.
U||A child so stout and strong that few would think
U||An hour might carry him to death’s dark brink,
U||Yet pale he lay, tho’ hidden was the cause,
U||And Galens search’d in vain thro’ Nature’s laws.
U||But stricken sadness could not quite suppress
U||The roving thought, or wrinkled grandam’s guess:
U||Tho’ spoke by stealth, ’twas known to half a score
U||That Dame De Blois rode by the day before;
U||She had (they said) with glances weird and wild
U||Paus’d by the gate to view the prattling child,
U||Nor did they like the smile which seem’d to trace
U||New lines of evil on her proud, dark face.
U||These things they whisper’d, when the mother’s cry
U||Told of the end—the gentle soul gone by;
U||In genuine grief the kindly watcher wept,
U||Whilst the lov’d babe with saints and angels slept.
U||The village priest his simple rites went thro’,
U||And good Michel nail’d up the box of yew;
U||Around the corpse the holy candles burn’d,
U||The mourners sighed, the parents dumbly yearn’d.
U||Then one by one each sought his humble bed,
U||And left the lonely mother with her dead.
U||Late in the night it was, when o’er the vale
U||The storm-king swept with pandemoniac gale;
U||Deep pil’d the cruel snow, yet strange to tell,
U||The lightning sputter’d while the white flakes fell;
U||A hideous presence seem’d abroad to steal,
U||And terror sounded in the thunder’s peal.
U||Within the house of grief the tapers glow’d
U||Whilst the poor mother bow’d beneath her load;
U||Her salty eyes too tired now to weep,
U||Too pain’d to see, too sad to close in sleep.
U||The clock struck three, above the tempest heard,
U||When something near the lifeless infant stirr’d;
U||Some slipp’ry thing, that flopp’d in awkward way,
U||And climb’d the table where the coffin lay;
U||With scaly convolutions strove to find
U||The cold, still clay that death had left behind.
U||The nodding mother hears—starts broad awake—
U||Empower’d to reason, yet too stunn’d to shake;
U||The pois’nous thing she sees, and nimbly foils
U||The ghoulish purpose of the quiv’ring coils:
U||With ready axe the serpent’s head she cleaves,
U||And thrills with savage triumph whilst she grieves.
U||The injur’d reptile hissing glides from sight,
U||And hides its cloven carcass in the night.
U||The weeks slipp’d by, and gossip’s tongue began
U||To call the Sieur De Blois an alter’d man;
U||With curious mien he oft would pace along
U||The village street, and eye the gaping throng.
U||Yet whilst he shew’d himself as ne’er before,
U||His wild-eyed lady was observ’d no more.
U||In course of time, ’twas scarce thought odd or ill
U||That he his ears with village lore should fill;
U||Nor was the town with special rumour rife
U||When he sought out the bailiff and his wife:
U||Their tale of sorrow, with its ghastly end,
U||Was told, indeed, by ev’ry wond’ring friend.
U||The Sieur heard all, and low’ring rode away,
U||Nor was he seen again for many a day.
U||When vernal sunshine shed its cheering glow,
U||And genial zephyrs blew away the snow,
U||To frighten’d swains a horror was reveal’d
U||In the damp herbage of a melting field.
U||There (half preserv’d by winter’s frigid bed)
U||Lay the dark Dame De Blois, untimely dead;
U||By some assassin’s stroke most foully slain,
U||Her shapely brow and temples cleft in twain.
U||Reluctant hands the dismal burden bore
U||To the stone arches of the husband’s door,
U||Where silent serfs the ghastly thing receiv’d,
U||Trembling with fright, but less amaz’d than griev’d;
U||The Sieur his dame beheld with blazing eyes,
U||And shook with anger, more than with surprise.
U||(At least ’tis thus the stupid peasants told
U||Their wide-mouth’d wives when they the tale unroll’d.)
U||The village wonder’d why De Blois had kept
U||His spouse’s loss unmention’d and unwept,
U||Nor were there lacking sland’rous tongues to claim
U||That the dark master was himself to blame.
U||But village talk could scarcely hope to solve
U||A crime so deep, and thus the months revolve:
U||The rural train repeat the gruesome tale,
U||And gape and marvel more than they bewail.
U||Swift flew the sun, and winter once again
U||With icy talons gripp’d the frigid plain.
U||December brought its store of Christmas cheer,
U||And grateful peasants hail’d the op’ning year;
U||But by the hearth as Candlemas drew nigh,
U||The whisp’ring ancients spoke of things gone by.
U||Few had forgot the dark demoniac lore
U||Of things that came the Candlemas before,
U||And many a crone intently eyed the house
U||Where dwelt the sadden’d bailiff and his spouse.
U||At last the day arriv’d, the sky o’erspread
U||With dark’ning messengers and clouds of lead;
U||Each neighb’ring grove Aeolian warnings sigh’d,
U||And thick’ning terrors broadcast seem’d to bide.
U||The good folk, tho’ they knew not why, would run
U||Swift past the bailiff’s door, the scene to shun;
U||Within the house the grieving couple wept,
U||And mourn’d the child who now forever slept.
U||On rush’d the dusk in doubly hideous form,
U||Borne on the pinions of the gath’ring storm;
U||Unusual murmurs fill’d the rainless wind,
U||The rising river lash’d the troubled shore;
U||Black thro’ the night the awful storm-god prowl’d,
U||And froze the list’ners’ life-blood as he howl’d;
U||Gigantic trees like supple rushes sway’d,
U||Whilst for his home the trembling cotter pray’d.
U||Now falls a sudden lull amidst the gale;
U||With less’ning force the circling currents wail;
U||Far down the stream that laves the neighb’ring mead
U||Burst a new ululation, wildly key’d;
U||The peasant train a frantic mien assume,
U||And huddle closer in the spectral gloom:
U||To each strain’d ear the truth too well is known,
U||For that dread sound can come from wolves alone!
U||The rustics close attend, when ere they think,
U||A lupine army swarms the river’s brink;
U||From out the waters leap a howling train
U||That rend the air, and scatter o’er the plain:
U||With flaming orbs the frothing creatures fly,
U||And chant with hellish voice their hungry cry.
U||First of the pack a mighty monster leaps
U||With fearless tread, and martial order keeps;
U||Th’ attendant wolves his yelping tones obey,
U||And form in columns for the coming fray:
U||No frighten’d swain they harm, but silent bound
U||With a fix’d purpose o’er the frozen ground.
U||Straight course the monsters thro’ the village street,
U||Unholy vigour in their flying feet;
U||Thro’ half-shut blinds the shelter’d peasants peer,
U||And wax in wonder as they lose in fear.
U||Th’ excited pack at last their goal perceive,
U||And the vex’d air with deaf’ning clamour cleave;
U||The churls, astonish’d, watch th’ unnatural herd
U||Flock round a cottage at the leader’s word:
U||Quick spreads the fearsome fact, by rumour blown,
U||That the doom’d cottage is the bailiff’s own!
U||Round and around the howling daemons glide,
U||Whilst the fierce leader scales the vine-clad side;
U||The frantic wind its horrid wail renews,
U||And mutters madly thro’ the lifeless yews.
U||In the frail house the bailiff calmly waits
U||The rav’ning horde, and trusts th’ impartial Fates,
U||But the wan wife revives with curious mien
U||Another monster and an older scene;
U||Amidst th’ increasing wind that rocks the walls,
U||The dame to him the serpent’s deed recalls:
U||Then as a nameless thought fills both their minds,
U||The bare-fang’d leader crashes thro’ the blinds.
U||Across the room, with murd’rous fury rife,
U||Leaps the mad wolf, and seizes on the wife;
U||With strange intent he drags his shrieking prey
U||Close to the spot where once the coffin lay.
U||Wilder and wilder roars the mounting gale
U||That sweeps the hills and hurtles thro’ the vale;
U||The ill-made cottage shakes, the pack without
U||Dance with new fury in demoniac rout.
U||Quick as his thought, the valiant bailiff stands
U||Above the wolf, a weapon in his hands;
U||The ready axe that serv’d a year before,
U||Now serves as well to slay one monster more.
U||The creature drops inert, with shatter’d head,
U||Full on the floor, and silent as the dead;
U||The rescu’d wife recalls the dire alarms,
U||And faints from terror in her husband’s arms.
U||But as he holds her, all the cottage quakes,
U||And with full force the titan tempest breaks:
U||Down crash the walls, and o’er their shrinking forms
U||Burst the mad revels of the storm of storms.
U||Th’ encircling wolves advance with ghastly pace,
U||Hunger and murder in each gleaming face,
U||But as they close, from out the hideous night
U||Flashes a bolt of unexpected light:
U||The vivid scene to ev’ry eye appears,
U||And peasants shiver with returning fears.
U||Above the wreck the scatheless chimney stays,
U||Its outline glimm’ring in the fitful rays,
U||Whilst o’er the hearth still hangs the household shrine,
U||The Saviour’s image and the Cross divine!
U||Round the blest spot a lambent radiance glows,
U||And shields the cotters from their stealthy foes:
U||Each monstrous creature marks the wondrous glare,
U||Drops, fades, and vanishes in empty air!
U||The village train with startled eyes adore,
U||And count their beads in rev’rence o’er and o’er.
U||Now fades the light, and dies the raging blast,
U||The hour of dread and reign of horror past.
U||Pallid and bruis’d, from out his toppled walls
U||The panting bailiff with his good wife crawls:
U||Kind hands attend them, whilst o’er all the town
U||A strange sweet peace of spirit settles down.
U||Wonder and fear are still’d in soothing sleep,
U||As thro’ the breaking clouds the moon rays peep.
U||Here paus’d the prattling grandam in her speech,
U||Confus’d with age, the tale half out of reach;
U||The list’ning guest, impatient for a clue,
U||Fears ’tis not one tale, but a blend of two;
U||He fain would know how far’d the widow’d lord
U||Whose eerie ways th’ initial theme afford,
U||And marvels that the crone so quick should slight
U||His fate, to babble of the wolf-wrack’d night.
U||The old wife, press’d, for greater clearness strives,
U||Nods wisely, and her scatter’d wits revives;
U||Yet strangely lingers on her latter tale
U||Of wolf and bailiff, miracle and gale.
U||When (quoth the crone) the dawn’s bright radiance bath’d
U||Th’ eventful scene, so late in terror swath’d,
U||The chatt’ring churls that sought the ruin’d cot
U||Found a new marvel in the gruesome spot.
U||From fallen walls a trail of gory red,
U||As of the stricken wolf, erratic led;
U||O’er road and mead the new-dript crimson wound,
U||Till lost amidst the neighb’ring swampy ground:
U||With wonder unappeas’d the peasants burn’d,
U||For what the quicksand takes is ne’er return’d.
U||Once more the grandam, with a knowing eye,
U||Stops in her tale, to watch a hawk soar by;
U||The weary list’ner, baffled, seeks anew
U||For some plain statement, or enlight’ning clue.
U||Th’ indulgent crone attends the puzzled plea,
U||Yet strangely mutters o’er the mystery.
U||The Sieur? Ah, yes—that morning all in vain
U||His shaking servants scour’d the frozen plain;
U||No man had seen him since he rode away
U||In silence on the dark preceding day.
U||His horse, wild-eyed with some unusual fright,
U||Came wand’ring from the river-bank that night.
U||His hunting-hound, that mourn’d with piteous woe,
U||Howl’d by the quicksand swamp, his grief to shew.
U||The village folk thought much, but utter’d less;
U||The servants’ search wore out in emptiness:
U||For Sieur De Blois (the old wife’s tale is o’er)
U||Was lost to mortal sight for evermore.
