U||Providence
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||Where bay and river tranquil blend,
U||And leafy hillsides rise,
U||The spires of Providence ascend
U||Against the ancient skies.
U||Here centuried domes of shining gold
U||Salute the morning’s glare,
U||While slanting gables, odd and old,
U||Are scatter’d here and there.
U||And in the narrow winding ways
U||That climb o’er slope and crest,
U||The magic of forgotten days
U||May still be found to rest.
U||A fanlight’s gleam, a knocker’s blow,
U||A glimpse of Georgian brick—
U||The sights and sounds of long ago
U||Where fancies cluster thick.
U||A flight of steps with iron rail,
U||A belfry looming tall,
U||A slender steeple, carv’d and pale,
U||A moss-grown garden wall.
U||A hidden churchyard’s crumbling proofs
U||Of man’s mortality,
U||A rotting wharf where gambrel roofs
U||Keep watch above the sea.
U||Square and parade, whose walls have tower’d
U||Full fifteen decades long
U||By cobbled ways ’mid trees embower’d,
U||And slighted by the throng.
U||Stone bridges spanning languid streams,
U||Houses perch’d on the hill,
U||And courts where mysteries and dreams
U||The brooding spirit fill.
U||Steep alley steps by vines conceal’d,
U||Where small-pan’d windows glow
U||At twilight on a bit of field
U||That chance has left below.
U||My Providence! What airy hosts
U||Turn still thy gilded vanes;
U||What winds of elf that with grey ghosts
U||People thine ancient lanes!
U||The chimes of evening as of old
U||Above thy valleys sound,
U||While thy stern fathers ’neath the mould
U||Make blest thy sacred ground.
U||Thou dream’st beside the waters there,
U||Unchang’d by cruel years;
U||A spirit from an age more fair
U||That shines behind our tears.
U||Thy twinkling lights each night I see,
U||Tho’ time and space divide;
U||For thou art of the soul of me,
U||And always at my side!
U|| 
