U||Poemata Minora, Volume II
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||Ode to Selene or Diana
U||Immortal Moon, in maiden splendour shine.
U||Dispense thy beams, divine Latona’s child.
U||Thy silver rays all grosser things define,
U||And hide harsh truth in sweet illusion mild.
U||In thy soft light, the city of unrest
U||That stands so squalid in thy brother’s glare
U||Throws off its habit, and in silence blest
U||Becomes a vision, sparkling bright and fair.
U||The modern world, with all it’s care & pain,
U||The smoky streets, the hideous clanging mills,
U||Face ’neath thy beams, Selene, and again
U||We dream like shepherds on Chaldæa’s hills.
U||Take heed, Diana, of my humble plea.
U||Convey me where my happiness may last.
U||Draw me against the tide of time’s rough sea
U||And let my sprirt rest amid the past.
U||To the Old Pagan Religion
U||Olympian gods! How can I let ye go
U||And pin my faith to this new Christian creed?
U||Can I resign the deities I know
U||For him who on a cross for man did bleed?
U||How in my weakness can my hopes depend
U||On one lone God, though mighty be his pow’r?
U||Why can Jove’s host no more assistance lend,
U||To soothe my pain, and cheer my troubled hour?
U||Are there no Dryads on these wooded mounts
U||O’er which I oft in desolation roam?
U||Are there no Naiads in these crystal founts?
U||Nor Nereids upon the Ocean foam?
U||Fast spreads the new; the older faith declines.
U||The name of Christ resounds upon the air.
U||But my wrack’d soul in solitude repines
U||And gives the Gods their last-receivèd pray’r.
U||On the Ruin of Rome
U||Low dost thou lie, O Rome, neath the foot of the Teuton
U||Slaves are thy men, and bent to the will of thy conqueror:
U||Wither hath gone, great city, the race that gave law to all nations,
U||Subdu’d the east and the west, and made them bow down to thy consuls.
U||Knew not defeat, but gave it to all who attack’d thee?
U||Dead! and replac’d by these wretches who cower in confusion
U||Dead! They who gave us this empire to guard and to live in
U||Rome, thou didst fall from thy pow’r with the proud race that made thee,
U||And we, base Italians, enjoy’d what we could not have builded.
U||To Pan
U||Seated in a woodland glen
U||By a shallow reedy stream
U||Once I fell a-musing, when
U||I was lull’d into a dream.
U||From the brook a shape arose
U||Half a man and half a goat.
U||Hoofs it had instead of toes
U||And a beard adorn’d its throat
U||On a set of rustic reeds
U||Sweetly play’d this hybrid man
U||Naught car’d I for earthly needs,
U||For I knew that this was Pan
U||Nymphs & Satyrs gather’d ’round
U||To enjoy the lively sound.
U||All to soon I woke in pain
U||And return’d to haunts of men.
U||But in rural vales I’d fain
U||Live and hear Pan’s pipes again.
U||On the Vanity of Human Ambition
U||Apollo, chasing Daphne, gain’d his prize
U||But lo! she turn’d to wood before his eyes.
U||More modern swains at golden prizes aim,
U||And ever strive some worldly thing to claim.
U||Yet ’tis the same as in Apollo’s case,
U||For, once attain’d, the purest gold seems base.
U||All that men seek ’s unworthy of the quest,
U||Yet seek they will, and never pause for rest.
U||True bliss, methinks, a man can only find
U||In virtuous life, & cultivated mind.
