U||The Poe-et’s Nightmare
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||A Fable
U||Luxus tumultus semper causa est.
U||Lucullus Languish, student of the skies,
U||And connoisseur of rarebits and mince pies,
U||A bard by choice, a grocer’s clerk by trade,
U||(Grown pessimist thro’ honours long delay’d),
U||A secret yearning bore, that he might shine
U||In breathing numbers, and in song divine.
U||Each day his fountain pen was wont to drop
U||An ode or dirge or two about the shop,
U||Yet naught could strike the chord within his heart
U||That throbb’d for poesy, and cry’d for art.
U||Each eve he sought his bashful Muse to wake
U||With overdoses of ice-cream and cake;
U||But thou’ th’ ambitious youth a dreamer grew,
U||Th’ Aonian Nymph declin’d to come to view.
U||Sometimes at dusk he scour’d the heav’ns afar,
U||Searching for raptures in the evening star;
U||One night he strove to catch a tale untold
U||In crystal deeps—but only caught a cold.
U||So pin’d Lucullus with his lofty woe,
U||Till one drear day he bought a set of Poe:
U||Charm’d with the cheerful horrors there display’d,
U||He vow’d with gloom to woo the Heav’nly Maid.
U||Of Auber’s tarn and Yaanek’s slope he dreams,
U||And weaves an hundred Ravens in his schemes.
U||Not far from our young hero’s peaceful home
U||Lies the fair grove wherein he loves to roam.
U||Tho’ but a stunted copse in vacant lot,
U||He dubs it Tempe, and adores the spot;
U||When shallow puddles dot the wooded plain,
U||And brim o’er muddy banks with muddy rain,
U||He calls them limpid lakes or poison pools
U||(Depending on which bard his fancy rules).
U||’Tis here he comes with Heliconian fire
U||On Sundays when he smites the Attic lyre;
U||And here one afternoon he brought his gloom,
U||Resolv’d to chant a poet’s lay of doom.
U||Roget’s Thesaurus, and a book of rhymes,
U||Provide the rungs whereon his spirit climbs:
U||With this grave retinue he trod the grove
U||And pray’d the Fauns he might a Poe-et prove.
U||But sad to tell, ere Pegasus flew high,
U||The not unrelish’d supper hour drew nigh;
U||Our tuneful swain th’ imperious call attends,
U||And soon above the groaning table bends.
U||Tho’ it were too prosaic to relate
U||Th’ exact particulars of what he ate
U||(Such long-drawn lists the hasty reader skips,
U||Like Homer’s well-known catalogue of ships),
U||This much we swear: that as adjournment near’d,
U||A monstrous lot of cake had disappear’d!
U||Soon to his chamber the young bard repairs,
U||And courts soft Somnus with sweet Lydian airs;
U||Thro’ open casement scans the star-strown deep,
U||And ’neath Orion’s beams sinks off to sleep.
U||Now start from airy dell the elfin train
U||That dance each midnight o’er the sleeping plain,
U||To bless the just, or cast a warning spell
U||On those who dine not wisely, but too well.
U||First Deacon Smith they plague, whose nasal glow
U||Comes from what Holmes hath call’d “Elixir Pro”;
U||Group’d round the couch his visage they deride,
U||Whilst thro’ his dreams unnumber’d serpents glide.
U||Next troop the little folk into the room
U||Where snores our young Endymion, swath’d in gloom:
U||A smile lights up his boyish face, whilst he
U||Dreams of the moon—or what he ate at tea.
U||The chieftain elf th’ unconscious youth surveys,
U||And on his form a strange enchantment lays:
U||Those lips, that lately thrill’d with frosted cake,
U||Uneasy sounds in slumbrous fashion make;
U||At length their owner’s fancies they rehearse,
U||And lisp this awesome Poe-em in blank verse:
U||Aletheia Phrikodes
U||Omnia risus et omnia pulvis et omnia nihil.
U||Demoniac clouds, up-pil’d in chasmy reach
U||Of soundless heav’n, smother’d the brooding night;
U||Nor came the wonted whisp’rings of the swamp,
U||Nor voice of autumn wind along the moor,
U||Nor mutter’d noises of th’ insomnious grove
U||Whose black recesses never saw the sun.
U||Within that grove a hideous hollow lies,
U||Half bare of trees; a pool in centre lurks
U||That none dares sound; a tarn of murky face
U||(Tho’ naught can prove its hue, since light of day,
U||Affrighted, shuns the forest-shadow’d banks).
U||Hard by, a yawning hillside grotto breathes,
U||From deeps unvisited, a dull, dank air
U||That sears the leaves on certain stunted trees
U||Which stand about, clawing the spectral gloom
U||With evil boughs. To this accursed dell
U||Come woodland creatures, seldom to depart:
U||Once I behold, upon a crumbling stone
U||Set altar-like before the cave, a thing
U||I saw not clearly, yet from glimpsing, fled.
U||In this half-dusk I meditate alone
U||At many a weary noontide, when without
U||A world forgets me in its sun-blest mirth.
U||Here howl by night the werewolves, and the souls
U||Of those that knew me well in other days.
U||Yet on this night the grove spake not to me;
U||Nor spake the swamp, nor wind along the moor,
U||Nor moan’d the wind about the lonely eaves
U||Of the bleak, haunted pile wherein I lay.
U||I was afraid to sleep, or quench the spark
U||Of the low-burning taper by my couch.
U||I was afraid when thro’ the vaulted space
U||Of the old tow’r, the clock-ticks died away
U||Into a silence so profound and chill
U||That my teeth chatter’d—giving yet no sound.
U||Then flicker’d low the light, and all dissolv’d,
U||Leaving me floating in the hellish grasp
U||Of body’d blackness, from whose beating wings
U||Came ghoulish blasts of charnel-scented mist.
U||Things vague, unseen, unfashion’d, and unnam’d
U||Jostled each other in the seething void
U||That gap’d, chaotic, downward to a sea
U||Of speechless horror, foul with writhing thoughts.
U||All this I felt, and felt the mocking eyes
U||Of the curs’d universe upon my soul;
U||Yet naught I saw nor heard, till flash’d a beam
U||Of lurid lustre thro’ the rotting heav’ns,
U||Playing on scenes I labour’d not to see.
U||Methought the nameless tarn, alight at last,
U||Reflected shapes, and more reveal’d within
U||Those shocking depths than ne’er were seen before;
U||Methought from out the cave a demon train,
U||Grinning and smirking, reel’d in fiendish rout;
U||Bearing within their reeking paws a load
U||Of carrion viands for an impious feast.
U||Methought the stunted trees with hungry arms
U||Grop’d greedily for things I dare not name;
U||The while a stifling, wraith-like noisomeness
U||Fill’d all the dale, and spoke a larger life
U||Of uncorporeal hideousness awake
U||In the half-sentient wholeness of the spot.
U||Now glow’d the ground, and tarn, and cave, and trees,
U||And moving forms, and things not spoken of,
U||With such a phosphorescence as men glimpse
U||In the putrescent thickets of the swamp
U||Where logs decaying lie, and rankness reigns.
U||Methought a fire-mist drap’d with lucent fold
U||The well-remember’d features of the grove,
U||Whilst whirling ether bore in eddying streams
U||The hot, unfinish’d stuff of nascent worlds
U||Hither and thither thro’ infinities
U||Of light and darkness, strangely intermix’d;
U||Wherein all entity had consciousness,
U||Without th’ accustom’d outward shape of life.
U||Of these swift-circling currents was my soul,
U||Free from the flesh, a true constituent part;
U||Nor felt I less myself, for want of form.
U||Then clear’d the mist, and o’er a star-strown scene,
U||Divine and measureless, I gaz’d in awe.
U||Alone in space, I view’d a feeble fleck
U||Of silvern light, marking the narrow ken
U||Which mortals call the boundless universe.
U||On ev’ry side, each as a tiny star,
U||Shone more creations, vaster than our own,
U||And teeming with unnumber’d forms of life;
U||Tho’ we as life would recognise it not,
U||Being bound to earthy thoughts of human mould.
U||As on a moonless night the Milky Way
U||In solid sheen displays its countless orbs
U||To weak terrestrial eyes, each orb a sun;
U||So beam’d the prospect on my wond’ring soul:
U||A spangled curtain, rich with twinkling gems,
U||Yet each a mighty universe of suns.
U||But as I gaz’d, I sens’d a spirit voice
U||In speech didactic, tho’ no voice it was,
U||Save as it carried thought. It bade me mark
U||That all the universes in my view
U||Form’d but an atom in infinity;
U||Whose reaches pass the ether-laden realms
U||Of heat and light, extending to far fields
U||Where flourish worlds invisible and vague,
U||Fill’d with strange wisdom and uncanny life,
U||And yet beyond; to myriad spheres of light,
U||To spheres of darkness, to abysmal voids
U||That know the pulses of disorder’d force.
U||Big with these musings, I survey’d the surge
U||Of boundless being, yet I us’d not eyes,
U||For spirit leans not on the props of sense.
U||The docent presence swell’d my strength of soul;
U||All things I knew, but knew with mind alone.
U||Time’s endless vista spread before my thought
U||With its vast pageant of unceasing change
U||And sempiternal strife of force and will;
U||I saw the ages flow in stately stream
U||Past rise and fall of universe and life;
U||I saw the birth of suns and worlds, their death,
U||Their transmutation into limpid flame,
U||Their second birth and second death, their course
U||Perpetual thro’ the aeons’ termless flight,
U||Never the same, yet born again to serve
U||The varying purpose of omnipotence.
U||And whilst I watch’d, I knew each second’s space
U||Was greater than the lifetime of our world.
U||Then turn’d my musings to that speck of dust
U||Whereon my form corporeal took its rise;
U||That speck, born but a second, which must die
U||In one brief second more; that fragile earth;
U||That crude experiment; that cosmic sport
U||Which holds our proud, aspiring race of mites
U||And moral vermin; those presuming mites
U||Whom ignorance with empty pomp adorns,
U||And misinstructs in specious dignity;
U||Those mites who, reas’ning outward, vaunt themselves
U||As the chief work of Nature, and enjoy
U||In fatuous fancy the particular care
U||Of all her mystic, super-regnant pow’r.
U||And as I strove to vision the sad sphere
U||Which lurk’d, lost in ethereal vortices,
U||Methough my soul, tun’d to the infinite,
U||Refus’d to glimpse that poor atomic blight;
U||That misbegotten accident of space;
U||That globe of insignificance, whereon
U||(My guide celestial told me) dwells no part
U||Of empyrean virtue, but where breed
U||The coarse corruptions of divine disease;
U||The fest’ring ailments of infinity;
U||The morbid matter by itself call’d man:
U||Such matter (said my guide) as oft breaks forth
U||On broad Creation’s fabric, to annoy
U||For a brief instant, ere assuaging death
U||Heal up the malady its birth provok’d.
U||Sicken’d, I turn’d my heavy thoughts away.
U||Then spake th’ ethereal guide with mocking mien,
U||Upbraiding me for searching after Truth;
U||Visiting on my mind the searing scorn
U||Of mind superior; laughing at the woe
U||Which rent the vital essence of my soul.
U||Methought he brought remembrance of the time
U||When from my fellows to the grove I stray’d,
U||In solitude and dusk to meditate
U||On things forbidden, and to pierce the veil
U||Of seeming good and seeming beauteousness
U||That covers o’er the tragedy of Truth,
U||Helping mankind forget his sorry lot,
U||And raising Hope where Truth would crush it down.
U||He spake, and as he ceas’d, methought the flames
U||Of fuming Heav’n resolv’d in torments dire;
U||Whirling in maelstroms of rebellious might,
U||Yet ever bound by laws I fathom’d not.
U||Cycles and epicycles, of such girth
U||That each a cosmos seem’d, dazzled my gaze
U||Till all a wild phantasmal glow became.
U||Now burst athwart the fulgent formlessness
U||A rift of purer sheen, a sight supernal,
U||Broader that all the void conceiv’d by man,
U||Yet narrow here. A glimpse of heav’ns beyond;
U||Of weird creations so remote and great
U||That ev’n my guide assum’d a tone of awe.
U||Borne on the wings of stark immensity,
U||A touch of rhythm celestial reach’d my soul;
U||Thrilling me more with horror than with joy.
U||Again the spirit mock’d my human pangs,
U||And deep revil’d me for presumptuous thoughts:
U||Yet changing now his mien, he bade me scan
U||The wid’ning rift that clave the walls of space;
U||He bade me search it for the ultimate;
U||He bade me find the Truth I sought so long;
U||He bade me brave th’ unutterable Thing,
U||The final Truth of moving entity.
U||All this he bade and offer’d—but my soul,
U||Clinging to life, fled without aim or knowledge,
U||Shrieking in silence thro’ the gibbering deeps.
U||Thus shriek’d the young Lucullus, as he fled
U||Thro’ gibbering deeps—and tumbled out of bed;
U||Within the room the morning sunshine gleams,
U||Whilst the poor youth recalls his troubled dreams.
U||He feels his aching limbs, whose woeful pain
U||Informs his soul his body lives again,
U||And thanks his stars—or cosmoses—or such
U||That he survives the noxious nightmare’s clutch.
U||Thrill’d with the music of th’ eternal spheres
U||(Or is it the alarm-clock that he hears?),
U||He vows to all the Pantheon, high and low,
U||No more to feed on cake, or pie, or Poe.
U||And now his gloomy spirits seem to rise,
U||As he the world beholds with clearer eyes;
U||The cup he thought too full of dregs to quaff
U||Affords him wine enough to raise a laugh.
U||(All this is metaphor—you must not think
U||Our late Endymion prone to stronger drink!)
U||With brighter visage and with lighter heart,
U||He turns his fancies to the grocer’s mart;
U||And strange to say, at last he seems to find
U||His daily duties worthy of his mind.
U||Since Truth prov’d such a high and dang’rous goal,
U||Our bard seeks one less trying to his soul;
U||With deep-drawn breath he flouts his dreary woes,
U||And a good clerk from a bad poet grows!
U||Now close attend my lay, ye scribbling crew
U||That bay the moon in numbers strange and new;
U||That madly for the spark celestial bawl
U||In metres short or long, or none at all:
U||Curb your rash force, in numbers or at tea,
U||Nor overzealous for high fancies be;
U||Reflect, ere ye the draught Pierian take,
U||What worthy clerks or plumbers ye might make;
U||Wax not too frenzied in the leaping line
U||That neither sense nor measure can confine,
U||Lest ye, like young Lucullus Launguish, groan
U||Beneath Poe-etic nightmares of your own!
U|| 
