U||The Peace Advocate
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||(Supposed to be a “pome,” but cast strictly in modern metre.)
U||The vicar sat in the firelight’s glow,
U||A volume in his hand;
U||And a tear he shed for the widespread woe,
U||And the anguish brought by the vicious foe
U||That overran the land.
U||But ne’er a hand for his King rais’d he,
U||For he was a man of peace;
U||And he car’d not a whit for the victory
U||That must come to preserve his nation free,
U||And the world from fear release.
U||His son had buckled on his sword,
U||The first at the front was he;
U||But the vicar his valiant child ignor’d,
U||And his noble deeds in the field deplor’d,
U||For he knew not bravery.
U||On his flock he strove to fix his will,
U||And lead them to scorn the fray.
U||He told them that conquest brings but ill;
U||That meek submission would serve them still
U||To keep the foe away.
U||In vain did he hear the bugle’s sound
U||That strove to avert the fall.
U||The land, quoth he, is all men’s ground,
U||What matter if friend or foe be found
U||As master of us all?
U||One day from the village green hard by
U||The vicar heard a roar
U||Of cannon that rivall’d the anguish’d cry
U||Of the hundreds that liv’d, but wish’d to die
U||As the enemy rode them o’er.
U||Now he sees his own cathedral shake
U||At the foeman’s wanton aim.
U||The ancient tow’rs with the bullets quake;
U||The steeples fall, the foundations break,
U||And the whole is lost in flame.
U||Up the vicarage lane file the cavalcade,
U||And the vicar, and daughter, and wife
U||Scream out in vain for the needed aid
U||That only a regiment might have made
U||Ere they lose what is more than life.
U||Then quick to his brain came manhood’s thought,
U||As he saw his erring course;
U||And the vicar his dusty rifle brought
U||That the foe might at least by one be fought,
U||And force repaid with force.
U||One shot—the enemy’s blasting fire
U||A breach in the wall cuts thro’,
U||But the vicar replies with his waken’d ire;
U||Fells one arm’d brute for each fallen spire,
U||And in blood is born anew.
U||Two shots—the wife and daughter sink,
U||Each with a mortal wound;
U||And the vicar, too madden’d by far to think,
U||Rushes boldly on to death’s vague brink,
U||With the manhood he has found.
U||Three shots—but shots of another kind
U||The smoky regions rend;
U||And upon the foeman with rage gone blind,
U||Like a ceaseless, resistless, avenging wind,
U||The rescuing troops descend.
U||The smoke-pall clears, and the vicar’s son
U||His father’s life has sav’d;
U||And the vicar looks o’er the ruin done,
U||Ere the vict’ry by his child was won,
U||His face with care engrav’d.
U||The vicar sat in the firelight’s glow,
U||The volume in his hand,
U||That brought to his hearth the bitter woe
U||Which only a husband and father can know,
U||And truly understand.
U||With a chasten’d mien he flung the book
U||To the leaping flames before;
U||And a breath of sad relief he took
U||As the pages blacken’d beneath his look—
U||The fool of Peace no more!
U||Epilogue
U||The rev’rend parson, wak’d to man’s estate,
U||Laments his wife’s and daughter’s common fate.
U||His martial son in warm embrace enfolds,
U||And clings the tighter to the child he holds.
U||His peaceful notions, banish’d in an hour,
U||Will nevermore his wit or sense devour;
U||But steep’d in truth, ’tis now his nobler plan
U||To cure, yet recognise, the faults of man.
U|| 
