U||Pacifist War Song—1917
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||We are the valiant Knights of Peace
U||Who prattle for the Right:
U||Our banner is of snowy fleece,
U||Inscribed: “TOO PROUD TO FIGHT!”
U||By sweet Chautauqua’s flow’ry banks
U||We love to sing and play,
U||But should we spy a foeman’s ranks,
U||We’d proudly run away!
U||When Prussian fury sweeps the main
U||Our freedom to deny;
U||Of tyrant laws we ne’er complain,
U||But gladsomely comply!
U||We do not fear the submarines
U||That plough the troubled foam;
U||We scorn the ugly old machines—
U||And safely stay at home!
U||They say our country’s close to war,
U||And soon must man the guns;
U||But we see naught to struggle for—
U||We love the gentle Huns!
U||What tho’ their hireling Greaser bands
U||Invade our southern plains?
U||We well can spare those boist’rous lands,
U||Content with what remains!
U||Our fathers were both rude and bold,
U||And would not live like brothers;
U||But we are of a finer mould—
U||We’re much more like our mothers!
U|| 
