U||The Outpost
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||When evening cools the yellow stream,
U||And shadows stalk the jungle’s ways,
U||Zimbabwe’s palace flares ablaze
U||For a great King who fears to dream.
U||For he alone of all mankind
U||Waded the swamp that serpents shun;
U||And struggling toward the setting sun,
U||Came on the veldt that lies behind.
U||No other eyes had vented there
U||Since eyes were lent for human sight—
U||But there, as sunset turned to night,
U||He found the Elder Secret’s lair.
U||Strange turrets rose beyond the plain,
U||And walls and bastions spread around
U||The distant domes that fouled the ground
U||Like leprous fungi after rain.
U||A grudging moon writhed up to shine
U||Past leagues where life can have no home;
U||And paling far-off tower and dome,
U||Shewed each unwindowed and malign.
U||Then he who in his boyhood ran
U||Through vine-hung ruins free of fear,
U||Trembled at what he saw—for here
U||Was no dead, ruined seat of man.
U||Inhuman shapes, half-seen, half-guessed,
U||Half solid and half ether-spawned,
U||Seethed down from starless voids that yawned
U||In heav’n, to these blank walls of pest.
U||And voidward from that pest-mad zone
U||Amorphous hordes seethed darkly back,
U||Their dim claws laden with the wrack
U||Of things that men have dreamed and known.
U||The ancient Fishers from Outside—
U||Were there not tales the high-priest told,
U||Of how they found the worlds of old,
U||And took what pelf their fancy spied?
U||Their hidden, dread-ringed outposts brood
U||Upon a million worlds of space;
U||Abhorred by every living race,
U||Yet scatheless in their solitude.
U||Sweating with fright, the watcher crept
U||Back to the swamp that serpents shun,
U||So that he lay, by rise of sun,
U||Safe in the palace where he slept.
U||None saw him leave, or come at dawn,
U||Nor does his flesh bear any mark
U||Of what he met in that curst dark—
U||Yet from his sleep all peace has gone.
U||When evening cools the yellow stream,
U||And shadows stalk the jungle’s ways,
U||Zimbabwe’s palace flares ablaze,
U||For a great King who fears to dream.
