U||On Receiving a Picture of Swans
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||With pensive grace the melancholy Swan
U||Mourns o’er the tomb of luckless Phaëton;
U||On grassy banks the weeping poplars wave,
U||And guard with tender care the wat’ry grave.
U||Would that I might, should I too proudly claim
U||An Heav’nly parent, or a Godlike fame,
U||When flown too high, and dash’d to depths below,
U||Receive such tribute as a Cygnus’ woe!
U||The faithful bird, that dumbly floats along,
U||Sighs all the deeper for his want of song.
U|| 
