U||Ode for July Fourth, 1917
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||As Columbia’s brave scions, in anger array’d,
U||Once defy’d a proud monarch and built a new nation;
U||’Gainst their brothers of Britain unsheath’d the sharp blade
U||That hath ne’er met defeat nor endur’d desecration;
U||So must we in this hour
U||Show our valour and pow’r,
U||And dispel the black perils that over us low’r:
U||Whilst the sons of Britannia, no longer our foes,
U||Will rejoice in our triumphs and strengthen our blows!
U||See the banners of Liberty float in the breeze
U||That plays light o’er the regions our fathers defended;
U||Hear the voice of the million resound o’er the leas,
U||As the deeds of the past are proclaim’d and commended;
U||And in splendour on high
U||Where our flags proudly fly,
U||See the folds we tore down flung again to the sky:
U||For the Emblem of England, in kinship unfurl’d,
U||Shall divide with Old Glory the praise of the world!
U||Bury’d now are the hatreds of subject and King,
U||And the strife that once sunder’d an Empire hath vanish’d.
U||With the fame of the Saxon the heavens shall ring
U||As the vultures of darkness are baffled and banish’d;
U||And the broad British sea,
U||Of her enemies free,
U||Shall in tribute bow gladly, Columbia to thee:
U||For the friends of the Right, in the field side by side,
U||Form a fabric of Freedom no hand can divide!
U|| 
