U||The Nightmare Lake
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||There is a lake in distant Zan,
U||Beyond the wonted haunts of man,
U||Where broods alone in a hideous state
U||A spirit dead and desolate;
U||A spirit ancient and unholy,
U||Heavy with fearsome melancholy,
U||Which from the waters dull and dense
U||Draws vapors cursed with pestilence.
U||Around the banks, a mire of clay,
U||Sprawl things offensive in decay,
U||And curious birds that reach that shore
U||Are seen by mortals nevermore.
U||Here shines by day the searing sun
U||On glassy wastes beheld by none,
U||And here by night pale moonbeams flow
U||Into the deeps that yawn below.
U||In nightmares only is it told
U||What scenes beneath those beams unfold;
U||What scenes, too old for human sight,
U||Lie sunken there in endless night;
U||For in those depths there only pace
U||The shadows of a voiceless race.
U||One midnight, redolent of ill,
U||I saw that lake, asleep and still;
U||While in the lurid sky there rode
U||A gibbous moon that glow’d and glow’d.
U||I saw the stretching marshy shore,
U||And the foul things those marshes bore:
U||Lizards and snakes convuls’d and dying;
U||Ravens and vampires putrefying;
U||All these, and hov’ring o’er the dead,
U||Narcophagi that on them fed.
U||And as the dreadful moon climb’d high,
U||Fright’ning the stars from out the sky,
U||I saw the lake’s dull water glow
U||Till sunken things appear’d below.
U||There shone unnumber’d fathoms down,
U||The tow’rs of a forgotten town;
U||The tarnish’d domes and mossy walls;
U||Weed-tangled spires and empty halls;
U||Deserted fanes and vaults of dread,
U||And streets of gold uncoveted.
U||These I beheld, and saw beside
U||A horde of shapeless shadows glide;
U||A noxious horde which to my glance
U||Seem’d moving in a hideous dance
U||Round slimy sepulchres that lay
U||Beside a never-travell’d way.
U||Straight from those tombs a heaving rose
U||That vex’d the waters’ dull repose,
U||While lethal shades of upper space
U||Howl’d at the moon’s sardonic face.
U||Then sank the lake within its bed,
U||Suck’d down to caverns of the dead,
U||Till from the reeking, new-stript earth
U||Curl’d foetid fumes of noisome birth.
U||About the city, nigh uncover’d,
U||The monstrous dancing shadows hover’d,
U||When lo! there oped with sudden stir
U||The portal of each sepulchre!
U||No ear may learn, no tongue may tell
U||What nameless horror then befell.
U||I see that lake—that moon agrin—
U||That city and the things within—
U||Waking, I pray that on that shore
U||The nightmare lake may sink no more!
U|| 
