U||Nemesis
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||Thro’ the ghoul-guarded gateways of slumber,
U||Past the wan-moon’d abysses of night,
U||I have liv’d o’er my lives without number,
U||I have sounded all things with my sight;
U||And I struggle and shriek ere the daybreak, being driven to madness with fright.
U||I have whirl’d with the earth at the dawning,
U||When the sky was a vaporous flame;
U||I have seen the dark universe yawning,
U||Where the black planets roll without aim;
U||Where they roll in their horror unheeded, without knowledge or lustre or name.
U||I had drifted o’er seas without ending,
U||Under sinister grey-clouded skies
U||That the many-fork’d lightning is rending,
U||That resound with hysterical cries;
U||With the moans of invisible daemons that out of the green waters rise.
U||I have plung’d like a deer thro’ the arches
U||Of the hoary primordial grove,
U||Where the oaks feel the presence that marches
U||And stalks on where no spirit dares rove;
U||And I flee from a thing that surrounds me, and leers thro’ dead branches above.
U||I have stumbled by cave-ridden mountains
U||That rise barren and bleak from the plain,
U||I have drunk of the fog-foetid fountains
U||That ooze down to the marsh and the main;
U||And in hot cursed tarns I have seen things I care not to gaze on again.
U||I have scann’d the vast ivy-clad palace,
U||I have trod its untenanted hall,
U||Where the moon writhing up from the valleys
U||Shews the tapestried things on the wall;
U||Strange figures discordantly woven, which I cannot endure to recall.
U||I have peer’d from the casement in wonder
U||At the mouldering meadows around,
U||At the many-roof’d village laid under
U||The curse of a grave-girdled ground;
U||And from rows of white urn-carven marble I listen intently for sound.
U||I have haunted the tombs of the ages,
U||I have flown on the pinions of fear
U||Where the smoke-belching Erebus rages,
U||Where the jokulls loom snow-clad and drear:
U||And in realms where the sun of the desert consumes what it never can cheer.
U||I was old when the Pharaohs first mounted
U||The jewel-deck’d throne by the Nile;
U||I was old in those epochs uncounted
U||When I, and I only, was vile;
U||And Man, yet untainted and happy, dwelt in bliss on the far Arctic isle.
U||Oh, great was the sin of my spirit,
U||And great is the reach of its doom;
U||Not the pity of Heaven can cheer it,
U||Nor can respite be found in the tomb:
U||Down the infinite aeons come beating the wings of unmerciful gloom.
U||Thro’ the ghoul-guarded gateways of slumber,
U||Past the wan-moon’d abysses of night,
U||I have liv’d o’er my lives without number,
U||I have sounded all things with my sight;
U||And I struggle and shriek ere the daybreak, being driven to madness with fright.
