U||Nathicana
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||It was in the pale garden of Zaïs;
U||The mist-shrouded gardens of Zaïs,
U||Where blossoms the white nephalotë,
U||The redolent herald of midnight.
U||There slumber the still lakes of crystal,
U||And streamlets that flow without murm’ring;
U||Smooth streamlets from caverns of Kathos
U||Where brood the calm spirits of twilight.
U||And over the lakes and the streamlets
U||Are bridges of pure alabaster,
U||White bridges all cunningly carven
U||With figures of fairies and daemons.
U||Here glimmer strange suns and strange planets,
U||And strange is the crescent Banapis
U||That sets ’yond the ivy-grown ramparts
U||Where thickens the dust of the evening.
U||Here fall the white vapours of Yabon;
U||And here in the swirl of vapours
U||I saw the divine Nathicana;
U||The garlanded, white Nathicana;
U||The slender, black-hair’d Nathicana;
U||The sloe-ey’d, red-lipp’d Nathicana;
U||The silver-voic’d, sweet Nathicana;
U||The pale-rob’d, belov’d Nathicana.
U||And ever was she my belovèd,
U||From ages when Time was unfashion’d;
U||From days when the stars were not fashion’d
U||Nor any thing fashion’d but Yabon.
U||And here dwelt we ever and ever,
U||The innocent children of Zaïs,
U||At peace in the paths and the arbours,
U||White-crown’d with the blest nephalotë.
U||How oft would we float in the twilight
U||O’er flow’r-cover’d pastures and hillsides
U||All white with the lowly astalthon;
U||The lowly yet lovely astalthon,
U||And dream in a world made of dreaming
U||The dreams that are fairer than Aidenn;
U||Bright dreams that are truer than reason!
U||So dream’d and so lov’d we thro’ ages,
U||Till came the curs’d season of Dzannin;
U||The daemon-damn’d season of Dzannin;
U||When red shone the suns and the planets,
U||And red gleamed the crescent Banapis,
U||And red fell the vapours of Yabon.
U||Then redden’d the blossoms and streamlets
U||And lakes that lay under the bridges,
U||And even the calm alabaster
U||Glow’d pink with uncanny reflections
U||Till all the carv’d fairies and daemons
U||Leer’d redly from the backgrounds of shadow.
U||Now redden’d my vision, and madly
U||I strove to peer thro’ the dense curtain
U||And glimpse the divine Nathicana;
U||The pure, ever-pale Nathicana;
U||The lov’d, the unchang’d Nathicana.
U||But vortex on vortex of madness
U||Beclouded my labouring vision;
U||My damnable, reddening vision
U||That built a new world for my seeing;
U||A new world of redness and darkness,
U||A horrible coma call’d living.
U||So now in this coma call’d living
U||I view the bright phantons of beauty;
U||The false, hollow phantoms of beauty
U||That cloak all the evils of Dzannin.
U||I view them with infinite longing,
U||So like do they seem to my lov’d one;
U||So shapely and fair like my lov’d one;
U||Yet foul from their eyes shines their evil;
U||Their cruel and pitiless evil,
U||More evil than Thaphron and Latgoz,
U||Twice ill for its gorgeous concealment.
U||And only in slumbers of midnight
U||Appears the lost maid Nathicana,
U||The pallid, the pure Nathicana,
U||Who fades at the glance of the dreamer.
U||Again and again do I seek her;
U||I woo with deep draughts of Plathotis,
U||Deep draughts brew’d in wine of Astarte
U||And strengthen’d with tears of long weeping.
U||I yearn for the gardens of Zaïs;
U||The lovely lost garden of Zaïs
U||Where blossoms the white nephalotë,
U||The redolent herald of midnight.
U||The last potent draught I am brewing;
U||A draught that the daemons delight in;
U||A draught that will banish the redness;
U||The horrible coma call’d living.
U||Soon, soon, if I fail not in brewing,
U||The redness and madness will vanish,
U||And deep in the worm-peopled darkness
U||Will rot the base chains that hav bound me.
U||Once more shall the gardens of Zaïs
U||Dawn white on my long-tortur’d vision,
U||And there midst the vapours of Yabon
U||Will stand the divine Nathicana;
U||The deathless, restor’d Nathicana
U||Whose like is not met with in living.
U|| 
