U||The Messenger
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||To Bertrand K. Hart, Esq.
U||The thing, he said, would come that night at three
U||From the old churchyard on the hill below;
U||But crouching by an oak fire’s wholesome glow,
U||I tried to tell myself it could not be.
U||Surely, I mused, it was a pleasantry
U||Devised by one who did not truly know
U||The Elder Sign, bequeathed from long ago,
U||That sets the fumbling forms of darkness free.
U||He had not meant it—no—but still I lit
U||Another lamp as starry Leo climbed
U||Out of the Seekonk, and a steeple chimed
U||Three—and the firelight faded, bit by bit.
U||Then at the door that cautious rattling came—
U||And the mad truth devoured me like a flame!
U|| 
