U||Lines on Gen. Robert Edward Lee
U||Born Jan. 19, 1807
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||“Si veris magna paratur
U||Fama bonis, et si successu nuda remoto
U||Inspicitur virtus, quicquid laudamus in ullo
U||Majorum, fortuna fuit.”
U||—Lucan.
U||Whilst martial echoes o’er the wave resound,
U||And Europe’s gore incarnadines the ground;
U||Today no foreign hero we bemoan,
U||But count the glowing virtues of our own!
U||Illustrious LEE! around whose honour’d name
U||Entwines a patriot’s and a Christian’s fame;
U||With whose just praise admiring nations ring,
U||And whom repenting foes contritely sing!
U||When first our land fraternal fury bore,
U||And Sumter’s guns alarm’d the anxious shore;
U||When Faction’s reign ancestral rights o’erthrew,
U||And sunder’d States a mutual hatred knew;
U||Then clash’d contending chiefs of kindred line,
U||In flesh to suffer and in fame to shine.
U||But o’er them all, majestic in his might,
U||Rose LEE, unrivall’d, to sublimest height:
U||With torturing choice defy’d opposing Fate,
U||And shunn’d Temptation for his native State!
U||Thus Washington his monarch’s rule o’erturn’d
U||When young Columbia with rebellion burn’d.
U||And what in Washington the world reveres,
U||In LEE with equal magnitude appears.
U||Our nation’s Father, crown’d with vict’ry’s bays,
U||Enjoys a loving land’s eternal praise:
U||Let, then, our hearts with equal rev’rence greet
U||His proud successor, rising o’er defeat!
U||Around his greatness pour disheartening woes,
U||But still he tow’rs above his conqu’ring foes.
U||Silence! ye jackal herd that vainly blame
U||Th’ unspotted leader by a traitor’s name:
U||If such was LEE, let blushing Justice mourn,
U||And trait’rous Liberty endure our scorn!
U||As Philopoemen once sublimely strove,
U||And earn’d declining Hellas’ thankful love;
U||So follow’d LEE the purest patriot’s part,
U||And wak’d the worship of the grateful heart:
U||The South her soul in body’d form discerns;
U||The North from LEE a nobler freedom learns!
U||Attend! ye sons of Albion’s ancient race,
U||Whate’er your country, and whate’er your place:
U||LEE’S valiant deeds, tho’ dear to Southern song,
U||To all our Saxon strain as well belong.
U||Courage like his the parent Island won,
U||And led an Empire past the setting sun;
U||To realms unknown our laws and language bore;
U||Rais’d England’s banner on the desert shore;
U||Crush’d the proud rival, and subdu’d the sea
U||For ages past, and aeons yet to be!
U||From Scotia’s hilly bounds the paean rolls,
U||And Afric’s distant Cape great LEE extols;
U||The sainted soul and manly mien combine
U||To grace Britannia’s and Virginia's line!
U||As dullards now in thoughtless fervour prate
U||Of shameful peace, and sing th’ unmanly State;
U||As churls their piping reprobations shriek,
U||And damn the heroes that protect the weak;
U||Let LEE’S brave shade the timid throng accost,
U||And give them back the manhood they have lost!
U||What kindlier spirit, breathing from on high,
U||Can teach us how to live and how to die?
U|| 
