U||Laeta; a Lament
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||Respectfully Dedicated to Rheinhart Kleiner, Esq.
U||With Compliments of the Author
U||How sad droop the willows by Zulal’s fair side,
U||Where so lately I stray’d with my raven-hair’d bride:
U||Ev’ry light-floating lily, each flow’r on the shore,
U||Folds in sorrow since Laeta can see them no more!
U||Oh, blest were the days when in childhood and hope
U||With my Laeta I rov’d o’er the blossom-clad slope,
U||Plucking white meadow-daisies and ferns by the stream,
U||As we laugh’d at the ripples that twinkle and gleam.
U||Not a bloom deck’d the mead that could rival in grace
U||The dear innocent charms of my Laeta’s fair face;
U||Not a thrush thrill’d the grove with a carol so choice
U||As the silvery strains of my Laeta’s sweet voice.
U||The shy Nymphs of the woodland, the fount and the plain,
U||Strove to equal her beauty, but strove all in vain;
U||Yet no envy they bore her, while fruitless they strove,
U||For so pure was my Laeta, they could only love!
U||When the warm breath of Auster play’d soft o’er the flow’rs,
U||And young Zephyrus rustled the gay scented bow’rs,
U||Ev’ry breeze seem’d to pause as it drew near the fair,
U||Too much aw’d at her sweetness to tumble her hair.
U||How fond were our dreams on the day when we stood
U||In the ivy-grown temple beside the dark wood;
U||When our pledges we seal’d at the sanctify’d shrine,
U||And I knew that my Laeta forever was mine!
U||How blissful our thoughts when the wild autumn came,
U||And the forests with scarlet and gold were aflame;
U||Yet how heavy my heart when I first felt the fear
U||That my starry-eyed Laeta would fade with the year!
U||The pastures were sere and the heavens were grey
U||When I laid my lov’d Laeta forever away,
U||And the river god pity’d, as weeping I pac’d
U||Mingling hot bitter tears with his cold frozen waste.
U||Now the flow’rs have return’d, but they bloom not so sweet
U||As in days when they blossom’d round Laeta’s dear feet;
U||And the willows complain to the answering hill,
U||And the thrushes that once were so happy are still.
U||The green meadows and groves in their loneliness pine,
U||Whilst the Dryads no more in their madrigals join,
U||The breeze once so joyous now murmurs and sighs,
U||And blows soft o’er the spot where my lov’d Laeta lies.
U||So pensive I roam o’er the desolate lawn
U||Where we wander’d and lov’d in the days that are gone,
U||And I yearn for the autumn, when Zulal’s blue tide
U||Shall sing low by my grave at the lov’d Laeta’s side.
U|| 
