U||The House
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||’Tis a grove-circled dwelling
U||Set close to a hill,
U||Where the branches are telling
U||Strange legends of ill;
U||Over timbers so old
U||That they breathe of the dead,
U||Crawl the vines, green and cold,
U||By strange nourishment fed;
U||And no man knows the juices they suck from the depths of their dank slimy bed.
U||In the gardens are growing
U||Tall blossoms and fair,
U||Each pallid bloom throwing
U||Perfume on the air;
U||But the afternoon sun
U||With its shining red rays
U||Makes the picture loom dun
U||On the curious gaze,
U||And above the sween scent of the the blossoms rise odours of numberless days.
U||The rank grasses are waving
U||On terrace and lawn,
U||Dim memories sav’ring
U||Of things that have gone;
U||The stones of the walks
U||Are encrusted and wet,
U||And a strange spirit stalks
U||When the red sun has set,
U||And the soul of the watcher is fill’d with faint pictures he fain would forget.
U||It was in the hot Junetime
U||I stood by that scene,
U||When the gold rays of noontime
U||Beat bright on the green.
U||But I shiver’d with cold,
U||Groping feebly for light,
U||As a picture unroll’d—
U||And my age-spanning sight
U||Saw the time I had been there before flash like fulgury out of the night.
U|| 
