U||Hallowe’en in a Suburb
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||The steeples are white in the wild moonlight,
U||And the trees have a silver glare;
U||Past the chimneys high see the vampires fly,
U||And the harpies of upper air,
U||That flutter and laugh and stare.
U||For the village dead to the moon outspread
U||Never shone in the sunset’s gleam,
U||But grew out of the deep that the dead years keep
U||Where the rivers of madness stream
U||Down the gulfs to a pit of dream.
U||A chill wind weaves thro’ the rows of sheaves
U||In the meadows that shimmer pale,
U||And comes to twine where the headstones shine
U||And the ghouls of the churchyard wail
U||For harvests that fly and fail.
U||Not a breath of the strange grey gods of change
U||That tore from the past its own
U||Can quicken this hour, when a spectral pow’r
U||Spreads sleep o’er the cosmic throne
U||And looses the vast unknown.
U||So here again stretch the vale and plain
U||That moons long-forgotten saw,
U||And the dead leap gay in the pallid ray,
U||Sprung out of the tomb’s black maw
U||To shake all the world with awe.
U||And all that the morn shall greet forlorn,
U||The ugliness and the pest
U||Of rows where thick rise the stones and brick,
U||Shall some day be with the rest,
U||And brood with the shades unblest.
U||Then wild in the dark let the lemurs bark,
U||And the leprous spires ascend;
U||For new and old alike in the fold
U||Of horror and death are penn’d,
U||For the hounds of Time to rend.
U|| 
