U||A Garden
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||There’s an ancient, ancient garden that I see sometimes in dreams,
U||Where the very Maytime sunlight plays and glows with spectral gleams;
U||Where the gaudy-tinted blossoms seem to wither into grey,
U||And the crumbling walls and pillars waken thoughts of yesterday.
U||There are vines in nooks and crannies, and there’s moss about the pool,
U||And the tangled weedy thicket chokes the arbour dark and cool:
U||In the silent sunken pathways springs an herbage sparse and spare,
U||Where the musty scent of dead things dulls the fragrance of the air.
U||There is not a living creature in the lonely space around,
U||And the hedge-encompass’d quiet never echoes to a sound.
U||As I walk, and wait, and listen, I will often seek to find
U||When it was I knew that garden in an age long left behind;
U||I will oft conjure a vision of a day that is no more,
U||As I gaze upon the grey, grey scenes I feel I knew before.
U||Then a sadness settles o’er me, and a tremor seems to start:
U||For I know the flow’rs are shrivell’d hopes—the garden is my heart!
U|| 
