U||Fungi from Yuggoth
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||I. The Book
U||The place was dark and dusty and half-lost
U||In tangles of old alleys near the quays,
U||Reeking of strange things brought in from the seas,
U||And with queer curls of fog that west winds tossed.
U||Small lozenge panes, obscured by smoke and frost,
U||Just shewed the books, in piles like twisted trees,
U||Rotting from floor to roof—congeries
U||Of crumbling elder lore at little cost.
U||I entered, charmed, and from a cobwebbed heap
U||Took up the nearest tome and thumbed it through,
U||Trembling at curious words that seemed to keep
U||Some secret, monstrous if one only knew.
U||Then, looking for some seller old in craft,
U||I could find nothing but a voice that laughed.
U||II. Pursuit
U||I held the book beneath my coat, at pains
U||To hide the thing from sight in such a place;
U||Hurrying through the ancient harbor lanes
U||With often-turning head and nervous pace.
U||Dull, furtive windows in old tottering brick
U||Peered at me oddly as I hastened by,
U||And thinking what they sheltered, I grew sick
U||For a redeeming glimpse of clean blue sky.
U||No one had seen me take the thing—but still
U||A blank laugh echoed in my whirling head,
U||And I could guess what nighted worlds of ill
U||Lurked in that volume I had coveted.
U||The way grew strange—the walls alike and madding—
U||And far behind me, unseen feet were padding.
U||III. The Key
U||I do not know what windings in the waste
U||Of those strange sea-lanes brought me home once more,
U||But on my porch I trembled, white with haste
U||To get inside and bolt the heavy door.
U||I had the book that told the hidden way
U||Across the void and through the space-hung screens
U||That hold the undimensioned worlds at bay,
U||And keep lost aeons to their own demesnes.
U||At last the key was mine to those vague visions
U||Of sunset spires and twilight woods that brood
U||Dim in the gulfs beyond this earth’s precisions,
U||Lurking as memories of infinitude.
U||The key was mine, but as I sat there mumbling,
U||The attic window shook with a faint fumbling.
U||IV. Recognition
U||The day had come again, when as a child
U||I saw—just once—that hollow of old oaks,
U||Grey with a ground-mist that enfolds and chokes
U||The slinking shapes which madness has defiled.
U||It was the same—an herbage rank and wild
U||Clings round an altar whose carved sign invokes
U||That Nameless One to whom a thousand smokes
U||Rose, aeons gone, from unclean towers up-piled.
U||I saw the body spread on that dank stone,
U||And knew those things which feasted were not men;
U||I knew this strange, grey world was not my own,
U||But Yuggoth, past the starry voids—and then
U||The body shrieked at me with a dead cry,
U||And all too late I knew that it was I!
U||V. Homecoming
U||The daemon said that he would take me home
U||To the pale, shadowy land I half recalled
U||As a high place of stair and terrace, walled
U||With marble balustrades that sky-winds comb,
U||While miles below a maze of dome on dome
U||And tower on tower beside a sea lies sprawled.
U||Once more, he told me, I would stand enthralled
U||On those old heights, and hear the far-off foam.
U||All this he promised, and through sunset’s gate
U||He swept me, past the lapping lakes of flame,
U||And red-gold thrones of gods without a name
U||Who shriek in fear at some impending fate.
U||Then a black gulf with sea-sounds in the night:
U||“Here was your home,” he mocked, “when you had sight!”
U||VI. The Lamp
U||We found the lamp inside those hollow cliffs
U||Whose chiseled sign no priest in Thebes could read,
U||And from whose caverns frightened hieroglyphs
U||Warned every living creature of earth’s breed.
U||No more was there—just that one brazen bowl
U||With traces of a curious oil within;
U||Fretted with some obscurely patterned scroll,
U||And symbols hinting vaguely of strange sin.
U||Little the fears of forty centuries meant
U||To us as we bore off our slender spoil,
U||And when we scanned it in our darkened tent
U||We struck a match to test the ancient oil.
U||It blazed—great God! . . . But the vast shapes we saw
U||In that mad flash have seared our lives with awe.
U||VII. Zaman’s Hill
U||The great hill hung close over the old town,
U||A precipice against the main street’s end;
U||Green, tall, and wooded, looking darkly down
U||Upon the steeple at the highway bend.
U||Two hundred years the whispers had been heard
U||About what happened on the man-shunned slope—
U||Tales of an oddly mangled deer or bird,
U||Or of lost boys whose kin had ceased to hope.
U||One day the mail-man found no village there,
U||Nor were its folk or houses seen again;
U||People came out from Aylesbury to stare—
U||Yet they all told the mail-man it was plain
U||That he was mad for saying he had spied
U||The great hill’s gluttonous eyes, and jaws stretched wide.
U||VIII. The Port
U||Ten miles from Arkham I had struck the trail
U||That rides the cliff-edge over Boynton Beach,
U||And hoped that just at sunset I could reach
U||The crest that looks on Innsmouth in the vale.
U||Far out at sea was a retreating sail,
U||White as hard years of ancient winds could bleach,
U||But evil with some portent beyond speech,
U||So that I did not wave my hand or hail.
U||Sails out of Innsmouth! echoing old renown
U||Of long-dead times. But now a too-swift night
U||Is closing in, and I have reached the height
U||Whence I so often scan the distant town.
U||The spires and roofs are there—but look! The gloom
U||Sinks on dark lanes, as lightless as the tomb!
U||IX. The Courtyard
U||It was the city I had known before;
U||The ancient, leprous town where mongrel throngs
U||Chant to strange gods, and beat unhallowed gongs
U||In crypts beneath foul alleys near the shore.
U||The rotting, fish-eyed houses leered at me
U||From where they leaned, drunk and half-animate,
U||As edging through the filth I passed the gate
U||To the black courtyard where the man would be.
U||The dark walls closed me in, and loud I cursed
U||That ever I had come to such a den,
U||When suddenly a score of windows burst
U||Into wild light, and swarmed with dancing men:
U||Mad, soundless revels of the dragging dead—
U||And not a corpse had either hands or head!
U||X. The Pigeon-Flyers
U||They took me slumming, where gaunt walls of brick
U||Bulge outward with a viscous stored-up evil,
U||And twisted faces, thronging foul and thick,
U||Wink messages to alien god and devil.
U||A million fires were blazing in the streets,
U||And from flat roofs a furtive few would fly
U||Bedraggled birds into the yawning sky
U||While hidden drums droned on with measured beats.
U||I knew those fires were brewing monstrous things,
U||And that those birds of space had been Outside—
U||I guessed to what dark planet’s crypts they plied,
U||And what they brought from Thog beneath their wings.
U||The others laughed—till struck too mute to speak
U||By what they glimpsed in one bird’s evil beak.
U||XI. The Well
U||Farmer Seth Atwood was past eighty when
U||He tried to sink that deep well by his door,
U||With only Eb to help him bore and bore.
U||We laughed, and hoped he’d soon be sane again.
U||And yet, instead, young Eb went crazy, too,
U||So that they shipped him to the county farm.
U||Seth bricked the well-mouth up as tight as glue—
U||Then hacked an artery in his gnarled left arm.
U||After the funeral we felt bound to get
U||Out to that well and rip the bricks away,
U||But all we saw were iron hand-holds set
U||Down a black hole deeper than we could say.
U||And yet we put the bricks back—for we found
U||The hole too deep for any line to sound.
U||XII. The Howler
U||They told me not to take the Briggs’ Hill path
U||That used to be the highroad through to Zoar,
U||For Goody Watkins, hanged in seventeen-four,
U||Had left a certain monstrous aftermath.
U||Yet when I disobeyed, and had in view
U||The vine-hung cottage by the great rock slope,
U||I could not think of elms or hempen rope,
U||But wondered why the house still seemed so new.
U||Stopping a while to watch the fading day,
U||I heard faint howls, as from a room upstairs,
U||When through the ivied panes one sunset ray
U||Struck in, and caught the howler unawares.
U||I glimpsed—and ran in frenzy from the place,
U||And from a four-pawed thing with human face.
U||XIII. Hesperia
U||The winter sunset, flaming beyond spires
U||And chimneys half-detached from this dull sphere,
U||Opens great gates to some forgotten year
U||Of elder splendours and divine desires.
U||Expectant wonders burn in those rich fires,
U||Adventure-fraught, and not untinged with fear;
U||A row of sphinxes where the way leads clear
U||Toward walls and turrets quivering to far lyres.
U||It is the land where beauty’s meaning flowers;
U||Where every unplaced memory has a source;
U||Where the great river Time begins its course
U||Down the vast void in starlit streams of hours.
U||Dreams bring us close—but ancient lore repeats
U||That human tread has never soiled these streets.
U||XIV. Star-Winds
U||It is a certain hour of twilight glooms,
U||Mostly in autumn, when the star-wind pours
U||Down hilltop streets, deserted out-of-doors,
U||But shewing early lamplight from snug rooms.
U||The dead leaves rush in strange, fantastic twists,
U||And chimney-smoke whirls round with alien grace,
U||Heeding geometries of outer space,
U||While Fomalhaut peers in through southward mists.
U||This is the hour when moonstruck poets know
U||What fungi sprout in Yuggoth, and what scents
U||And tints of flowers fill Nithon’s continents,
U||Such as in no poor earthly garden blow.
U||Yet for each dream these winds to us convey,
U||A dozen more of ours they sweep away!
U||XV. Antarktos
U||Deep in my dream the great bird whispered queerly
U||Of the black cone amid the polar waste;
U||Pushing above the ice-sheet lone and drearly,
U||By storm-crazed aeons battered and defaced.
U||Hither no living earth-shapes take their courses,
U||And only pale auroras and faint suns
U||Glow on that pitted rock, whose primal sources
U||Are guessed at dimly by the Elder Ones.
U||If men should glimpse it, they would merely wonder
U||What tricky mound of Nature’s build they spied;
U||But the bird told of vaster parts, that under
U||The mile-deep ice-shroud crouch and brood and bide.
U||God help the dreamer whose mad visions shew
U||Those dead eyes set in crystal gulfs below!
U||XVI. The Window
U||The house was old, with tangled wings outthrown,
U||Of which no one could ever half keep track,
U||And in a small room somewhat near the back
U||Was an odd window sealed with ancient stone.
U||There, in a dream-plagued childhood, quite alone
U||I used to go, where night reigned vague and black;
U||Parting the cobwebs with a curious lack
U||Of fear, and with a wonder each time grown.
U||One later day I brought the masons there
U||To find what view my dim forbears had shunned,
U||But as they pierced the stone, a rush of air
U||Burst from the alien voids that yawned beyond.
U||They fled—but I peered through and found unrolled
U||All the wild worlds of which my dreams had told.
U||XVII. A Memory
U||There were great steppes, and rocky table-lands
U||Stretching half-limitless in starlit night,
U||With alien campfires shedding feeble light
U||On beasts with tinkling bells, in shaggy bands.
U||Far to the south the plain sloped low and wide
U||To a dark zigzag line of wall that lay
U||Like a huge python of some primal day
U||Which endless time had chilled and petrified.
U||I shivered oddly in the cold, thin air,
U||And wondered where I was and how I came,
U||When a cloaked form against a campfire’s glare
U||Rose and approached, and called me by my name.
U||Staring at that dead face beneath the hood,
U||I ceased to hope—because I understood.
U||XVIII. The Gardens of Yin
U||Beyond that wall, whose ancient masonry
U||Reached almost to the sky in moss-thick towers,
U||There would be terraced gardens, rich with flowers,
U||And flutter of bird and butterfly and bee.
U||There would be walks, and bridges arching over
U||Warm lotos-pools reflecting temple eaves,
U||And cherry-trees with delicate boughs and leaves
U||Against a pink sky where the herons hover.
U||All would be there, for had not old dreams flung
U||Open the gate to that stone-lanterned maze
U||Where drowsy streams spin out their winding ways,
U||Trailed by green vines from bending branches hung?
U||I hurried—but when the wall rose, grim and great,
U||I found there was no longer any gate.
U||XIX. The Bells
U||Year after year I heard that faint, far ringing
U||Of deep-toned bells on the black midnight wind;
U||Peals from no steeple I could ever find,
U||But strange, as if across some great void winging.
U||I searched my dreams and memories for a clue,
U||And thought of all the chimes my visions carried;
U||Of quiet Innsmouth, where the white gulls tarried
U||Around an ancient spire that once I knew.
U||Always perplexed I heard those far notes falling,
U||Till one March night the bleak rain splashing cold
U||Beckoned me back through gateways of recalling
U||To elder towers where the mad clappers tolled.
U||They tolled—but from the sunless tides that pour
U||Through sunken valleys on the sea’s dead floor.
U||XX. Night-Gaunts
U||Out of what crypt they crawl, I cannot tell,
U||But every night I see the rubbery things,
U||Black, horned, and slender, with membraneous wings,
U||And tails that bear the bifid barb of hell.
U||They come in legions on the north wind’s swell,
U||With obscene clutch that titillates and stings,
U||Snatching me off on monstrous voyagings
U||To grey worlds hidden deep in nightmare’s well.
U||Over the jagged peaks of Thok they sweep,
U||Heedless of all the cries I try to make,
U||And down the nether pits to that foul lake
U||Where the puffed shoggoths splash in doubtful sleep.
U||But oh! If only they would make some sound,
U||Or wear a face where faces should be found!
U||XXI. Nyarlathotep
U||And at the last from inner Egypt came
U||The strange dark One to whom the fellahs bowed;
U||Silent and lean and cryptically proud,
U||And wrapped in fabrics red as sunset flame.
U||Throngs pressed around, frantic for his commands,
U||But leaving, could not tell what they had heard;
U||While through the nations spread the awestruck word
U||That wild beasts followed him and licked his hands.
U||Soon from the sea a noxious birth began;
U||Forgotten lands with weedy spires of gold;
U||The ground was cleft, and mad auroras rolled
U||Down on the quaking citadels of man.
U||Then, crushing what he chanced to mould in play,
U||The idiot Chaos blew Earth’s dust away.
U||XXII. Azathoth
U||Out in the mindless void the daemon bore me,
U||Past the bright clusters of dimensioned space,
U||Till neither time nor matter stretched before me,
U||But only Chaos, without form or place.
U||Here the vast Lord of All in darkness muttered
U||Things he had dreamed but could not understand,
U||While near him shapeless bat-things flopped and fluttered
U||In idiot vortices that ray-streams fanned.
U||They danced insanely to the high, thin whining
U||Of a cracked flute clutched in a monstrous paw,
U||Whence flow the aimless waves whose chance combining
U||Gives each frail cosmos its eternal law.
U||“I am His Messenger,” the daemon said,
U||As in contempt he struck his Master’s head.
U||XXIII. Mirage
U||I do not know if ever it existed—
U||That lost world floating dimly on Time’s stream—
U||And yet I see it often, violet-misted,
U||And shimmering at the back of some vague dream.
U||There were strange towers and curious lapping rivers,
U||Labyrinths of wonder, and low vaults of light,
U||And bough-crossed skies of flame, like that which quivers
U||Wistfully just before a winter’s night.
U||Great moors led off to sedgy shores unpeopled,
U||Where vast birds wheeled, while on a windswept hill
U||There was a village, ancient and white-steepled,
U||With evening chimes for which I listen still.
U||I do not know what land it is—or dare
U||Ask when or why I was, or will be, there.
U||XXIV. The Canal
U||Somewhere in dream there is an evil place
U||Where tall, deserted buildings crowd along
U||A deep, black, narrow channel, reeking strong
U||Of frightful things whence oily currents race.
U||Lanes with old walls half meeting overhead
U||Wind off to streets one may or may not know,
U||And feeble moonlight sheds a spectral glow
U||Over long rows of windows, dark and dead.
U||There are no footfalls, and the one soft sound
U||Is of the oily water as it glides
U||Under stone bridges, and along the sides
U||Of its deep flume, to some vague ocean bound.
U||None lives to tell when that stream washed away
U||Its dream-lost region from the world of clay.
U||XXV. St. Toad’s
U||“Beware St. Toad’s cracked chimes!” I heard him scream
U||As I plunged into those mad lanes that wind
U||In labyrinths obscure and undefined
U||South of the river where old centuries dream.
U||He was a furtive figure, bent and ragged,
U||And in a flash had staggered out of sight,
U||So still I burrowed onward in the night
U||Toward where more roof-lines rose, malign and jagged.
U||No guide-book told of what was lurking here—
U||But now I heard another old man shriek:
U||“Beware St. Toad’s cracked chimes!” And growing weak,
U||I paused, when a third greybeard croaked in fear:
U||“Beware St. Toad’s cracked chimes!” Aghast, I fled—
U||Till suddenly that black spire loomed ahead.
U||XXVI. The Familiars
U||John Whateley lived about a mile from town,
U||Up where the hills began to huddle thick;
U||We never thought his wits were very quick,
U||Seeing the way he let his farm run down.
U||He used to waste his time on some queer books
U||He’d found around the attic of his place,
U||Till funny lines got creased into his face,
U||And folks all said they didn’t like his looks.
U||When he began those night-howls we declared
U||He’d better be locked up away from harm,
U||So three men from the Aylesbury town farm
U||Went for him—but came back alone and scared.
U||They’d found him talking to two crouching things
U||That at their step flew off on great black wings.
U||XXVII. The Elder Pharos
U||From Leng, where rocky peaks climb bleak and bare
U||Under cold stars obscure to human sight,
U||There shoots at dusk a single beam of light
U||Whose far blue rays make shepherds whine in prayer.
U||They say (though none has been there) that it comes
U||Out of a pharos in a tower of stone,
U||Where the last Elder One lives on alone,
U||Talking to Chaos with the beat of drums.
U||The Thing, they whisper, wears a silken mask
U||Of yellow, whose queer folds appear to hide
U||A face not of this earth, though none dares ask
U||Just what those features are, which bulge inside.
U||Many, in man’s first youth, sought out that glow,
U||But what they found, no one will ever know.
U||XXVIII. Expectancy
U||I cannot tell why some things hold for me
U||A sense of unplumbed marvels to befall,
U||Or of a rift in the horizon’s wall
U||Opening to worlds where only gods can be.
U||There is a breathless, vague expectancy,
U||As of vast ancient pomps I half recall,
U||Or wild adventures, uncorporeal,
U||Ecstasy-fraught, and as a day-dream free.
U||It is in sunsets and strange city spires,
U||Old villages and woods and misty downs,
U||South winds, the sea, low hills, and lighted towns,
U||Old gardens, half-heard songs, and the moon’s fires.
U||But though its lure alone makes life worth living,
U||None gains or guesses what it hints at giving.
U||XXIX. Nostalgia
U||Once every year, in autumn’s wistful glow,
U||The birds fly out over an ocean waste,
U||Calling and chattering in a joyous haste
U||To reach some land their inner memories know.
U||Great terraced gardens where bright blossoms blow,
U||And lines of mangoes luscious to the taste,
U||And temple-groves with branches interlaced
U||Over cool paths—all these their vague dreams shew.
U||They search the sea for marks of their old shore—
U||For the tall city, white and turreted—
U||But only empty waters stretch ahead,
U||So that at last they turn away once more.
U||Yet sunken deep where alien polyps throng,
U||The old towers miss their lost, remembered song.
U||XXX. Background
U||I never can be tied to raw, new things,
U||For I first saw the light in an old town,
U||Where from my window huddled roofs sloped down
U||To a quaint harbour rich with visionings.
U||Streets with carved doorways where the sunset beams
U||Flooded old fanlights and small window-panes,
U||And Georgian steeples topped with gilded vanes—
U||These were the sights that shaped my childhood dreams.
U||Such treasures, left from times of cautious leaven,
U||Cannot but loose the hold of flimsier wraiths
U||That flit with shifting ways and muddled faiths
U||Across the changeless walls of earth and heaven.
U||They cut the moment’s thongs and leave me free
U||To stand alone before eternity.
U||XXXI. The Dweller
U||It had been old when Babylon was new;
U||None knows how long it slept beneath that mound,
U||Where in the end our questing shovels found
U||Its granite blocks and brought it back to view.
U||There were vast pavements and foundation-walls,
U||And crumbling slabs and statues, carved to shew
U||Fantastic beings of some long ago
U||Past anything the world of man recalls.
U||And then we saw those stone steps leading down
U||Through a choked gate of graven dolomite
U||To some black haven of eternal night
U||Where elder signs and primal secrets frown.
U||We cleared a path—but raced in mad retreat
U||When from below we heard those clumping feet.
U||XXXII. Alienation
U||His solid flesh had never been away,
U||For each dawn found him in his usual place,
U||But every night his spirit loved to race
U||Through gulfs and worlds remote from common day.
U||He had seen Yaddith, yet retained his mind,
U||And come back safely from the Ghooric zone,
U||When one still night across curved space was thrown
U||That beckoning piping from the voids behind.
U||He waked that morning as an older man,
U||And nothing since has looked the same to him.
U||Objects around float nebulous and dim—
U||False, phantom trifles of some vaster plan.
U||His folk and friends are now an alien throng
U||To which he struggles vainly to belong.
U||XXXIII. Harbour Whistles
U||Over old roofs and past decaying spires
U||The harbour whistles chant all through the night;
U||Throats from strange ports, and beaches far and white,
U||And fabulous oceans, ranged in motley choirs.
U||Each to the other alien and unknown,
U||Yet all, by some obscurely focussed force
U||From brooding gulfs beyond the Zodiac’s course,
U||Fused into one mysterious cosmic drone.
U||Through shadowy dreams they send a marching line
U||Of still more shadowy shapes and hints and views;
U||Echoes from outer voids, and subtle clues
U||To things which they themselves cannot define.
U||And always in that chorus, faintly blent,
U||We catch some notes no earth-ship ever sent.
U||XXXIV. Recapture
U||The way led down a dark, half-wooded heath
U||Where moss-grey boulders humped above the mould,
U||And curious drops, disquieting and cold,
U||Sprayed up from unseen streams in gulfs beneath.
U||There was no wind, nor any trace of sound
U||In puzzling shrub, or alien-featured tree,
U||Nor any view before—till suddenly,
U||Straight in my path, I saw a monstrous mound.
U||Half to the sky those steep sides loomed upspread,
U||Rank-grassed, and cluttered by a crumbling flight
U||Of lava stairs that scaled the fear-topped height
U||In steps too vast for any human tread.
U||I shrieked—and knew what primal star and year
U||Had sucked me back from man’s dream-transient sphere!
U||XXXV. Evening Star
U||I saw it from that hidden, silent place
U||Where the old wood half shuts the meadow in.
U||It shone through all the sunset’s glories—thin
U||At first, but with a slowly brightening face.
U||Night came, and that lone beacon, amber-hued,
U||Beat on my sight as never it did of old;
U||The evening star—but grown a thousandfold
U||More haunting in this hush and solitude.
U||It traced strange pictures on the quivering air—
U||Half-memories that had always filled my eyes—
U||Vast towers and gardens; curious seas and skies
U||Of some dim life—I never could tell where.
U||But now I knew that through the cosmic dome
U||Those rays were calling from my far, lost home.
U||XXXVI. Continuity
U||There is in certain ancient things a trace
U||Of some dim essence—more than form or weight;
U||A tenuous aether, indeterminate,
U||Yet linked with all the laws of time and space.
U||A faint, veiled sign of continuities
U||That outward eyes can never quite descry;
U||Of locked dimensions harbouring years gone by,
U||And out of reach except for hidden keys.
U||It moves me most when slanting sunbeams glow
U||On old farm buildings set against a hill,
U||And paint with life the shapes which linger still
U||From centuries less a dream than this we know.
U||In that strange light I feel I am not far
U||From the fixt mass whose sides the ages are.
