U||Festival
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||There is snow on the ground,
U||And the valleys are cold,
U||And a midnight profound
U||Blackly squats o’er the wold;
U||But a light on the hilltops half-seen hints of feastings unhallow’d and old.
U||There is death in the clouds,
U||There is fear in the night,
U||For the dead in their shrouds
U||Hail the sun’s turning flight,
U||And chant wild in the woods as they dance round a Yule-altar fungous and white.
U||To no gale of earth’s kind
U||Sways the forest of oak,
U||Where the sick boughs entwin’d
U||By mad mistletoes choke,
U||For these pow’rs are the pow’rs of the dark, from the graves of the lost Druid-folk.
U||And mayst thou to such deeds
U||Be an abbot and priest,
U||Singing cannibal greeds
U||At each devil-wrought feast,
U||And to all the incredulous world shewing dimly the sign of the beast.
