U||Fact and Fancy
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||How dull the wretch, whose philosophic mind
U||Disdains the pleasures of fantastic kind;
U||Whose prosy thoughts the joys of life exclude,
U||And wreck the solace of the poet’s mood!
U||Young Zeno, practic’d in the Stoic’s art,
U||Rejects the language of the glowing heart;
U||Dissolves sweet Nature to a mess of laws;
U||Condemns th’ effect whilst looking for the cause;
U||Freezes poor Ovid in an ic’d review,
U||And sneers because his fables are untrue!
U||In search of Truth the hopeful zealot goes,
U||But all the sadder tums, the more he knows!
U||Stay! vandal sophist, whose deep lore would blast
U||The graceful legends of the story’d past;
U||Whose tongue in censure flays th’ embellish’d page,
U||And scolds the comforts of a dreary age:
U||Would’st strip the foliage from the vital bough
U||Till all men grow as wisely dull as thou?
U||Happy the man whose fresh, untainted eye
U||Discerns a Pantheon in the spangled sky;
U||Finds Sylphs and Dryads in the waving trees,
U||And spies soft Notus in the southern breeze;
U||For whom the stream a cheering carol sings,
U||While reedy music by the fountain rings;
U||To whom the waves a Nereid tale confide
U||Till friendly presence fills the rising tide.
U||Happy is he, who void of learning’s woes,
U||Th’ ethereal life of body’d Nature knows:
U||I scorn the sage that tells me it but seems,
U||And flout his gravity in sunlit dreams!
U|| 
