U||Despair
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||O’er the midnight moorlands crying,
U||Thro’ the cypress forests sighing,
U||In the night-wind madly flying,
U||Hellish forms with streaming hair;
U||In the barren branches creaking,
U||By the stagnant swamp-pools speaking,
U||Past the shore-cliffs ever shrieking;
U||Damn’d daemons of despair.
U||Once, I think I half remember,
U||Ere the grey skies of November
U||Quench’d my youth’s aspiring ember,
U||Liv’d there such a thing as bliss;
U||Skies that now are dark were beaming,
U||Gold and azure, splendid seeming
U||Till I learn’d it all was dreaming—
U||Deadly drowsiness of Dis.
U||But the stream of Time, swift flowing,
U||Brings the torment of half-knowing—
U||Dimly rushing, blindly going
U||Past the never-trodden lea;
U||And the voyager, repining,
U||Sees the wicked death-fires shining,
U||Hears the wicked petrel’s whining
U||As he helpless drifts to sea.
U||Evil wings in ether beating;
U||Vultures at the spirit eating;
U||Things unseen forever fleeting
U||Black against the leering sky.
U||Ghastly shades of bygone gladness,
U||Clawing fiends of future sadness,
U||Mingle in a cloud of madness
U||Ever on the soul to lie.
U||Thus the living, lone and sobbing,
U||In the throes of anguish throbbing,
U||With the loathsome Furies robbing
U||Night and noon of peace and rest.
U||But beyond the groans and grating
U||Of abhorrent Life, is waiting
U||Sweet Oblivion, culminating
U||All the years of fruitless quest.
U|| 
