U||The Conscript
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||I am a peaceful working man—
U||I am not wise or strong—
U||But I can follow Nature’s plan
U||In labour, rest, and song.
U||One day the men that rule us all
U||Decided we must die,
U||Else pride and freedom surely fall
U||In the dim bye and bye.
U||They told me I must write my name
U||Upon a scroll of death;
U||That some day I should rise to fame
U||By giving up my breath.
U||I do not know what I have done
U||That I should thus be bound
U||To wait for tortures one by one,
U||And then an unmark’d mound.
U||I hate no man, and yet they say
U||That I must fight and kill;
U||That I must suffer day by day
U||To please a master’s will.
U||I used to have a conscience free,
U||But now they bid it rest;
U||They’ve made a number out of me,
U||And I must ne’er protest.
U||They tell of trenches, long and deep,
U||Fill’d with the mangled slain;
U||They talk till I can scarcely sleep,
U||So reeling is my brain.
U||They tell of filth, and blood, and woe;
U||Of things beyond belief;
U||Of things that make me tremble so
U||With mingled fright and grief.
U||I do not know what I shall do—
U||Is not the law unjust?
U||I can’t do what they want me to,
U||And yet they say I must!
U||Each day my doom doth nearer bring;
U||Each day the State prepares;
U||Sometimes I feel a watching thing
U||That stares, and stares, and stares.
U||I never seem to sleep—my head
U||Whirls in the queerest way.
U||Why am I chosen to be dead
U||Upon some fateful day?
U||Yet hark—some fibre is o’erwrought—
U||A giddying wine I quaff—
U||Things seem so odd, I can do naught
U||But laugh, and laugh, and laugh!
U|| 
