U||The City
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||It was golden and splendid,
U||That City of light;
U||A vision suspended
U||In deeps of the night;
U||A region of wonder and glory, whose temples were marble and white.
U||I remember the season
U||It dawn’d on my gaze;
U||The mad time of unreason,
U||The brain-numbing days
U||When Winter, white-sheeted and ghastly, stalks onward to torture and craze.
U||More lovely than Zion
U||It shone in the sky,
U||When the beams of Orion
U||Beclouded my eye,
U||Bringing sleep that was fill’d with dim mem’ries of moments obscure and gone by.
U||Its mansions were stately
U||With carvings made fair,
U||Each rising sedately
U||On terraces rare,
U||And the gardens were fragrant and bright with strange miracles blossoming there.
U||The avenues lur’d me
U||With vistas sublime;
U||Tall arches assur’d me
U||That once on a time
U||I had wander’d in rapture beneath them, and bask’d in the Halcyon clime.
U||On the plazas were standing
U||A sculptur’d array;
U||Long-bearded, commanding,
U||Grave men in their day—
U||But one stood dismantled and broken, its bearded face batter’d away.
U||In that city effulgent
U||No mortal I saw;
U||But my fancy, indulgent
U||To memory’s law,
U||Linger’d long on the forms in the plazas, and eyed their stone features with awe.
U||I fann’d the faint ember
U||That glow’d in my mind,
U||And strove to remember
U||The aeons behind;
U||To rove thro’ infinity freely, and visit the past unconfin’d.
U||Then the horrible warning
U||Upon my soul sped
U||Like the ominous morning
U||That rises in red,
U||And in panic I flew from the knowledge of terrors forgotten and dead.
U|| 
