U||The Cats
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||Babels of blocks to the high heavens tow’ring,
U||Flames of futility swirling below;
U||Poisonous fungi in brick and stone flow’ring,
U||Lanterns that shudder and death-lights that glow.
U||Black monstrous bridges across oily rivers,
U||Cobwebs of cable by nameless things spun;
U||Catacomb deeps whose dank chaos delivers
U||Streams of live foetor, that rots in the sun.
U||Colour and splendour, disease and decaying,
U||Shrieking and ringing and scrambling insane,
U||Rabbles exotic to stranger-gods praying,
U||Jumbles of odour that stifle the brain.
U||Legions of cats from the alleys nocturnal,
U||Howling and lean in the glare of the moon,
U||Screaming the future with mouthings infernal,
U||Yelling the burden of Pluto’s red rune.
U||Tall tow’rs and pyramids ivy’d and crumbling,
U||Bats that swoop low in the weed-cumber’d streets;
U||Bleak broken bridges o’er rivers whose rumbling
U||Joins with no voice as the thick tide retreats.
U||Belfries that blackly against the moon totter,
U||Caverns whose mouths are by mosses effac’d,
U||And living to answer the wind and the water,
U||Only the lean cats that howl in the waste!
U|| 
