U||The Ancient Track
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||There was no hand to hold me back
U||That night I found the ancient track
U||Over the hill, and strained to see
U||The fields that teased my memory.
U||This tree, that wall—I knew them well,
U||And all the roofs and orchards fell
U||Familiarly upon my mind
U||As from a past not far behind.
U||I knew what shadows would be cast
U||When the late moon came up at last
U||From back of Zaman’s Hill, and how
U||The vale would shine three hours from now.
U||And when the path grew steep and high,
U||And seemed to end against the sky,
U||I had no fear of what might rest
U||Beyond that silhouetted crest.
U||Straight on I walked, while all the night
U||Grew pale with phosphorescent light,
U||And wall and farmhouse gable glowed
U||Unearthly by the climbing road.
U||There was the milestone that I knew—
U||“Two miles to Dunwich”—now the view
U||Of distant spire and roofs would dawn
U||With ten more upward paces gone. . . .
U||There was no hand to hold me back
U||That night I found the ancient track,
U||And reached the crest to see outspread
U||A valley of the lost and dead:
U||And over Zaman’s Hill the horn
U||Of a malignant moon was born,
U||To light the weeds and vines that grew
U||On ruined walls I never knew.
U||The fox-fire glowed in field and bog,
U||And unknown waters spewed a fog
U||Whose curling talons mocked the thought
U||That I had ever known this spot.
U||Too well I saw from the mad scene
U||That my loved past had never been—
U||Nor was I now upon the trail
U||Descending to that long-dead vale.
U||Around was fog—ahead, the spray
U||Of star-streams in the Milky Way. . . .
U||There was no hand to hold me back
U||That night I found the ancient track.
U|| 
