U||An American to Mother England
U||By H. P. Lovecraft
U||England! My England! Can the surging sea
U||That lies between us tear my heart from thee?
U||Can distant birth and distant dwelling drain
U||Th’ ancestral blood that warms the loyal vein?
U||Isle of my Fathers! hear the filial song
U||Of him whose sources but to thee belong!
U||World-conquering Mother! by thy mighty hand
U||Was carv’d from savage wilds my native land:
U||Thy matchless sons the firm foundation laid;
U||Thy matchless arts the nascent nation made:
U||By thy just laws the young republic grew,
U||And thro’ thy greatness, kindred greatness knew:
U||What man that springs from thy untainted line
U||But sees Columbia’s virtues all as thine?
U||Whilst nameless multitudes upon our shore
U||From the dim corners of creation pour,
U||Whilst mongrel slaves crawl hither to partake
U||Of Saxon liberty they could not make,
U||From such an alien crew in grief I turn,
U||And for the mother’s voice of Britain burn.
U||England! Can aught remove the cherish’d chain
U||That binds my spirit to thy blest domain?
U||Can Revolution’s bitter precepts sway
U||The soul that must the ties of race obey?
U||Create a new Columbia if ye will;
U||The flesh that forms me is Britannic still!
U||Hail! oaken shades, and meads of dewy green,
U||So oft in sleep, yet ne’er in waking seen.
U||Peal out, ye ancient chimes, from vine-clad tow’r
U||Where pray’d my fathers in a vanish’d hour:
U||What countless years of rev’rence can ye claim
U||From bygone worshippers that bore my name!
U||Their forms are crumbling in the vaults around,
U||Whilst I, across the sea, but dream the sound.
U||Return, Sweet Vision! Let me glimpse again
U||The stone-built abbey, rising o’er the plain;
U||The neighb’ring village with its sun-show’r’d square;
U||The shaded mill-stream, and the forest fair,
U||The hedge-lin’d lane, that leads to rustic cot
U||Where sweet contentment is the peasant’s lot;
U||The mystic grove, by Druid wraiths possess’d,
U||The flow’ring fields, with fairy-castles blest:
U||And the old manor-house, sedate and dark,
U||Set in the shadows of the wooded park.
U||Can this be dreaming? Must my eyelids close
U||That I may catch the fragrance of the rose?
U||Is it in fancy that the midnight vale
U||Thrills with the warblings of the nightingale?
U||A golden moon bewitching radiance yields,
U||And England’s fairies trip o’er England’s fields.
U||England! Old England! in my love for thee
U||No dream is mine, but blessed memory;
U||Such haunting images and hidden fires
U||Course with the bounding blood of British sires:
U||From British bodies, minds, and souls I come,
U||And from them draw the vision of their home.
U||Awake, Columbia! scorn the vulgar age
U||That bids thee slight thy lordly heritage.
U||Let not the wide Atlantic’s wildest wave
U||Burst the blest bonds that fav’ring Nature gave:
U||Connecting surges ’twixt the nations run,
U||Our Saxon souls dissolving into one!
U|| 
